const a = [
  {"id":3651,"text":"Which of the following types of necrosis is seen in a granulomatous infection by Mycobacterium tuberculosis?","explanation":"In a granulomatous infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the characteristic type of necrosis observed is **caseous necrosis**. Caseous necrosis is a form of coagulative necrosis characterized by the formation of a cheese-like, friable material within the affected tissue.\r\n\r\nThe term \"caseous\" refers to the gross appearance of the necrotic tissue, which resembles a soft, white, crumbly mass resembling cheese. This type of necrosis is typically seen in chronic infections, particularly those caused by certain pathogens such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis. In tuberculosis, the immune response leads to the formation of granulomas, which are aggregates of immune cells, including macrophages, surrounded by a rim of lymphocytes. The central area of the granuloma undergoes caseous necrosis, forming a central necrotic core surrounded by the granulomatous inflammation.\r\n\r\nThe presence of caseous necrosis is a hallmark feature of tuberculosis and helps in the diagnosis of the disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Gangrenous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous granulomatous necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-caseating granuloma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3782,"text":"Coagulation factors are proteins that flow in the blood in their inactivated form. During a vessel injury, they become activated. Thrombin and thrombomodulin complex inactivates which of the following factors?","explanation":"During the process of coagulation, thrombin plays a central role in converting fibrinogen into fibrin, forming a blood clot. However, thrombin also has anticoagulant properties when it forms a complex with thrombomodulin, which is expressed on the surface of endothelial cells. When thrombin binds to thrombomodulin, it undergoes a conformational change and switches its function from a procoagulant to an anticoagulant.\r\n\r\nThe thrombin-thrombomodulin complex activates **protein C**, which is a natural anticoagulant protein present in the blood. Activated protein C, along with its cofactor protein S, then acts as a serine protease and inactivates several coagulation factors, including **factor V** and **factor VIII**. This inactivation process helps regulate and control the coagulation cascade, preventing excessive clot formation and maintaining the balance between clotting and clot dissolution.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"V and VIII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"II and III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IX and X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IX and VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3863,"text":"The specialized epithelium is present in which of the following lymphoid organ?","explanation":"The **thymus** is a primary lymphoid organ located in the upper chest, behind the sternum. It plays a crucial role in the development and maturation of T-lymphocytes, a type of white blood cell involved in cell-mediated immunity.\r\n\r\nThe thymus is characterized by a unique structure composed of two distinct regions: the cortex and the medulla. The cortex contains densely packed thymocytes, which are immature T-cells undergoing development and selection. Surrounding the thymocytes is a specialized epithelium known as the **thymic epithelium**, which provides a supportive environment for T-cell maturation.\r\n\r\nThe thymic epithelium consists of two main types of cells: cortical epithelial cells and medullary epithelial cells. These cells play a crucial role in promoting T-cell development, regulating the selection and maturation of T-cells, and preventing the development of self-reactive T-cells.","reference":"Alawam AS, Anderson G, Lucas B. Generation and regeneration of thymic epithelial cells. Frontiers in Immunology. Published May 7, 2020. Accessed May 29, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7221188/","responses":[{"text":"Thymus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tonsils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoid tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4014,"text":"A 5-year-old boy comes to the outpatient department complaining of a painful and swollen knee. On examination, bleeding is seen within the knee joint but with no signs of physical trauma. His mother gives a family history of a maternal uncle who recently died of a bleeding disorder. Investigations show isolated increased APTT. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is an X-linked recessive disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of coagulation factor VIII.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of a painful and swollen joint without a history of physical trauma suggests an intra-articular hemorrhage. Hemophilia A leads to impaired blood clotting, specifically due to a deficiency of factor VIII, which is involved in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation. As a result, patients with hemophilia A are prone to prolonged APTT (activated partial thromboplastin time).\r\n\r\nThe X-linked inheritance pattern explains the family history of a maternal uncle with a bleeding disorder. Hemophilia A predominantly affects males, while females are usually carriers of the disease.\r\n\r\nConfirmatory laboratory tests may include specific assays to measure factor VIII activity or genetic testing to identify mutations in the factor VIII gene.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662-663.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic uremic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4045,"text":"Innate immunity is considered to be the first line of defense against many microorganisms. Its major component includes which of the following?","explanation":"Innate immunity is the first line of defense against pathogens and plays a crucial role in protecting the body from infection. One of its major components is the **skin**.\r\n\r\nThe skin acts as a physical barrier that prevents the entry of microorganisms and foreign substances into the body. It consists of multiple layers of epithelial cells that are tightly packed together, making it difficult for pathogens to penetrate. Additionally, the skin produces antimicrobial substances such as defensins and cathelicidins, which have antimicrobial properties and help in destroying invading microorganisms.\r\n\r\nInnate immunity also includes other components such as **mucous membranes**, which line the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and genitourinary tracts and secrete mucus that traps and removes pathogens. **Phagocytes** (such as neutrophils and macrophages) are another important component of innate immunity, as they engulf and destroy pathogens through phagocytosis.\r\n\r\nWhile B-cells, T-cells, and antibodies are part of the adaptive immune response, the skin is a critical component of the innate immune system, providing a physical barrier and other defense mechanisms against pathogens.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 459.","responses":[{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4047,"text":"A girl comes to the outpatient department with complaints of epistaxis and small bruising on her skin. While giving her history she informs the physician that her sister has the same problem. Laboratory analysis shows that her partial thromboplastin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) are normal but prolonged bleeding time. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Bernard-Soulier syndrome (BSS)** is a rare inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of the glycoprotein complex **GPIb-IX-V** on platelets.\r\n\r\nThe clinical features of BSS include mucocutaneous bleeding, such as epistaxis (nosebleeds), easy bruising, and prolonged bleeding after minor injuries. Laboratory analysis typically reveals normal **partial thromboplastin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)**, which indicates the normal function of the intrinsic and common coagulation pathways. However, the **bleeding time** is prolonged due to impaired platelet adhesion and aggregation.\r\n\r\nThe underlying defect in BSS lies in the deficiency or dysfunction of the GPIb-IX-V complex, which plays a crucial role in mediating platelet adhesion to von Willebrand factor (vWF) on damaged blood vessel walls. Without proper platelet adhesion, hemostasis is compromised, leading to a tendency for bleeding.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that Hemophilia A and Hemophilia B are characterized by deficiencies of clotting factors VIII and IX, respectively, which would manifest as abnormal PT and aPTT results.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 117, 119, 660.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 433-434.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bernard-Soulier syndrome (BSS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4055,"text":"Raynaud's phenomenon and fibrosis of GI tract, skin, and tissues are symptoms of which of the following?","explanation":"**Systemic sclerosis** is a chronic autoimmune connective tissue disorder characterized by excessive fibrosis and vascular abnormalities. It primarily affects the skin, but it can also involve various organs such as the GI tract, lungs, kidneys, and heart.\r\n\r\nRaynaud's phenomenon, characterized by episodic vasospasm of the digital arteries in response to cold or stress, is a common early manifestation of systemic sclerosis. Fibrosis of the GI tract can lead to symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, acid reflux, and impaired absorption of nutrients.\r\n\r\nThe exact cause of systemic sclerosis is unknown, but it involves dysregulation of the immune system and activation of fibroblasts, leading to excessive production of collagen and deposition of extracellular matrix components.\r\n\r\nPolymyositis is an inflammatory muscle disease, DiGeorge syndrome is a congenital immunodeficiency disorder, multiple sclerosis is a demyelinating disease of the central nervous system, and Marfan's syndrome is a genetic disorder affecting connective tissue. None of these conditions exhibit the specific symptoms described in the question.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 228.","responses":[{"text":"Polymyositis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4343,"text":"Activation of which of the following factors results in the initiation of the coagulation cascade through the intrinsic pathway?","explanation":"The activation of **Factor XII** (also known as Hageman factor) results in the initiation of the coagulation cascade through the intrinsic pathway. Factor XII is a clotting factor that plays a key role in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation.\r\n\r\nIn the intrinsic pathway, Factor XII is activated by contact with negatively charged surfaces, such as exposed collagen or subendothelial structures. Once activated, Factor XII initiates a cascade of reactions that ultimately lead to the formation of a blood clot. This cascade involves the activation of several other clotting factors, including Factor XI, Factor IX, and Factor VIII.\r\n\r\nActivation of the intrinsic pathway is important for amplifying the coagulation process and forming a stable blood clot. It occurs primarily in response to vascular injury or exposure of blood to foreign surfaces.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Factor XII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4425,"text":"Most of the iron in the storage pool is in the form of which of the following?","explanation":"The majority of iron in the storage pool is in the form of **ferritin**. Ferritin is an intracellular protein complex that serves as an iron storage molecule. It is found in cells, particularly in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow. Ferritin stores iron in a non-toxic and readily available form.\r\n\r\nWhen iron levels are high, excess iron is bound to ferritin and stored within cells. As iron demand increases, ferritin releases iron to meet the body's needs. This allows for a regulated release of iron into the bloodstream for transportation to sites of utilization.\r\n\r\nHemosiderin, another iron storage complex, is derived from ferritin. It is an insoluble and aggregated form of ferritin that accumulates in cells during periods of iron overload or when there is an imbalance in iron metabolism.\r\n\r\nTransferrin is a transport protein that binds to iron in the bloodstream and delivers it to cells. Apotransferrin refers to transferrin without bound iron.\r\n\r\nWhile some iron may exist as free ions, the majority is bound to ferritin within the storage pool.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 874.","responses":[{"text":"Apotransferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Free iron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4438,"text":"What is the composition of hemoglobin A (HbA)?","explanation":"**Hemoglobin A (HbA)**, which is the predominant hemoglobin in adult humans, is composed of two alpha (α) chains and two beta (β) chains. Therefore, the correct composition of HbA is **α2, β2**.\r\n\r\nEach α chain is encoded by two genes (α1 and α2) located on chromosome 16, and each β chain is encoded by a single gene located on chromosome 11. The α and β chains come together to form a globin protein complex, which binds to heme molecules. The heme molecules contain iron ions, which allow for the reversible binding of oxygen.\r\n\r\nThe composition of hemoglobin can vary during different stages of development and in certain conditions. For example, during fetal development, hemoglobin F (HbF) is predominant and is composed of two alpha chains and two gamma (γ) chains. However, in adults, HbA is the major hemoglobin and is responsible for oxygen transport in the body.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 27.","responses":[{"text":"α2, γ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, β2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, δ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β2, γ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"γ2, ε2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4458,"text":"What is the composition of hemoglobin F (HbF)?","explanation":"**Hemoglobin F (HbF)** is the predominant hemoglobin during fetal development. It is composed of two alpha (α) chains and two gamma (γ) chains, making its composition **α2, γ2**.\r\n\r\nThe α chains are encoded by two genes (α1 and α2) located on chromosome 16, while the γ chains are encoded by a single gene located on chromosome 11. The combination of these chains forms the globin protein complex, which binds to heme molecules. The heme molecules contain iron ions, which enable the binding and transport of oxygen.\r\n\r\nHbF has a higher affinity for oxygen compared to adult hemoglobin (HbA), which allows for efficient oxygen transfer across the placenta from the mother to the fetus. After birth, the production of HbF decreases, and the production of HbA increases.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 33.","responses":[{"text":"α2, β2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"γ2, ε2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β2, γ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, γ2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, δ2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4509,"text":"A person undergoes ileal resection. After some days he develops weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia. Which anemia can it possibly be?","explanation":"After ileal resection, the absorption of vitamin B12 is impaired since the ileum is responsible for the absorption of this essential vitamin. Vitamin B12 is required for the synthesis of DNA and normal red blood cell maturation. Therefore, a deficiency of vitamin B12 leads to **megaloblastic anemia**.\r\n\r\nMegaloblastic anemia is characterized by the presence of large, immature red blood cells (megaloblasts) in the bone marrow. These cells have impaired DNA synthesis, leading to delayed maturation. The result is fewer and larger red blood cells in circulation.\r\n\r\nClinical manifestations of megaloblastic anemia include weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia symptoms due to decreased oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. Other symptoms may include pale skin, fatigue, and neurological manifestations such as numbness and tingling in the extremities.\r\n\r\nSupplementation of vitamin B12 is necessary to correct the deficiency and alleviate the symptoms of megaloblastic anemia.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 45.","responses":[{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic blood loss anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4512,"text":"Myoglobin is a pigment. Which system of the body does it have a role in?","explanation":"**Myoglobin** is a pigment that plays a crucial role in the respiratory system. It is a protein found primarily in muscle cells, particularly in the skeletal and cardiac muscles. Myoglobin functions as an oxygen-binding molecule, storing and releasing oxygen within muscle tissues.\r\n\r\nDuring muscle contraction, oxygen is required to support the energy demands of the muscle cells. Myoglobin acts as an oxygen reservoir, allowing efficient oxygen delivery to the muscle cells. It has a higher affinity for oxygen compared to hemoglobin, enabling it to readily bind and release oxygen within the muscle fibers.\r\n\r\nThe presence of myoglobin in muscle tissues enhances the oxygen supply and utilization during exercise and periods of increased metabolic demand. This ensures adequate oxygen delivery for energy production and muscle function.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"Central nervous system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electron transport chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary system","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4518,"text":"Hemostasis is a means of preventing blood loss. Whenever an injury occurs, which one of the following is the first step towards clotting?","explanation":"**Vasoconstriction** is indeed the first step in hemostasis, triggered immediately after injury to blood vessels. When a blood vessel is damaged, the smooth muscle in its walls constricts, causing the vessel to narrow. This vasoconstriction serves two primary purposes in hemostasis.\r\n\r\nFirst, vasoconstriction reduces blood flow to the injured area, which helps to minimize blood loss. The constriction of the vessel lumen decreases the amount of blood flowing through the damaged vessel, thus decreasing the hydrostatic pressure and the force pushing blood out of the vessel.\r\n\r\nSecond, vasoconstriction helps to expose the damaged endothelium to the bloodstream for platelet adhesion and activation. As the vessel constricts, the exposed endothelial cells release substances that promote platelet adhesion and initiate the formation of the platelet plug.\r\n\r\nTherefore, vasoconstriction is an essential initial response that occurs in the early stages of hemostasis to reduce blood flow and facilitate platelet plug formation at the site of injury.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 477.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of coagulation cascade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of platelet plug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of fibrin plug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retraction of the platelet plug","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4521,"text":"Which interleukin is required for the growth and proliferation of all the stem cells?","explanation":"**Interleukin-3 (IL-3)** is a cytokine that plays a crucial role in the growth and proliferation of stem cells. IL-3 is produced by various cells, including activated T cells and mast cells, and acts on hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. \r\n\r\nIL-3 stimulates the production and differentiation of multiple blood cell lineages, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. It acts as a growth factor for early progenitor cells, promoting their survival, proliferation, and differentiation into specific cell types. By supporting the growth of stem cells, IL-3 helps to maintain a healthy and functional hematopoietic system.\r\n\r\nWhile other interleukins, such as IL-1, IL-4, IL-5, and IL-2, also play important roles in immune regulation and hematopoiesis, IL-3 is specifically known for its broad effects on stem cell growth and proliferation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-3","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4541,"text":"Which of the following mucin antigens is present in both ovarian and breast cancers?","explanation":"**MUC-1** is the mucin antigen that is present in both ovarian and breast cancers. MUC-1, also known as **mucin 1** or **CA 15-3**, is a glycoprotein that is aberrantly expressed in various types of cancers, including ovarian and breast cancers.\r\n\r\nMUC-1 plays a role in protecting and lubricating epithelial surfaces. In normal tissues, it is expressed on the apical surface of glandular and ductal epithelial cells. However, in cancer cells, MUC-1 is overexpressed and undergoes structural changes, leading to increased cell adhesion, invasion, and metastasis.\r\n\r\nThe detection of MUC-1 antigen in serum can be used as a tumor marker for monitoring disease progression and response to treatment in ovarian and breast cancers. It is commonly measured using the CA 15-3 assay for breast cancer and the CA-125 assay for ovarian cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 312.","responses":[{"text":"CA19-9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CA-125","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MUC-1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4544,"text":"During the development of the spleen, mesenchymal cells are present between which layers?","explanation":"During the development of the spleen, mesenchymal cells are present between the **two layers of the dorsal mesogastrium**. The dorsal mesogastrium is a double-layered peritoneal fold that extends from the posterior abdominal wall to the developing stomach. It divides the abdominal cavity into the greater and lesser peritoneal sacs.\r\n\r\nWithin the dorsal mesogastrium, the mesenchymal cells undergo differentiation and give rise to the various components of the developing spleen. These components include the splenic parenchyma, blood vessels, and the connective tissue framework.\r\n\r\nAs development progresses, the dorsal mesogastrium undergoes further modifications, leading to the formation of the lienorenal ligament and the attachment of the spleen to the posterior abdominal wall.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 237.","responses":[{"text":"The two layers of ventral mesogastrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral and dorsal mesogastrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral mesogastrium and septum transversarium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The two layers of dorsal mesogastrium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal mesogastrium and septum transversarium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4545,"text":"When the total storage iron is much greater than the apoferritin storage pool, the extra iron is stored in an insoluble form. This form is known as which of the following?","explanation":"**Hemosiderin** is an aggregate of ferritin molecules that have become partially denatured and insoluble. It is found in tissues and cells involved in iron storage, such as the liver, spleen, and bone marrow.\r\n\r\nHemosiderin appears as golden-brown granules when stained and is a visual marker of iron overload or excessive iron deposition in tissues. It represents an accumulated iron reserve that can be mobilized when needed.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, ferritin is the soluble form of iron storage. It is a protein complex that binds and sequesters iron in a non-toxic form. Ferritin serves as the primary intracellular storage for iron, while hemosiderin acts as a backup storage system when ferritin levels are overwhelmed.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8748,"text":"Erythropoietin is primarily formed in which organ?","explanation":"**Erythropoietin (EPO)** is primarily formed in the **kidneys**, specifically in the interstitial cells located in the peritubular capillaries of the renal cortex and outer medulla. A small amount of EPO is also produced in the liver.\r\n\r\nEPO is a glycoprotein hormone that plays a crucial role in regulating red blood cell production. It stimulates the production of red blood cells from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. EPO is released in response to decreased oxygen levels in the blood, detected by specialized cells in the kidneys called peritubular fibroblasts. Hypoxia-inducible factor (HIF) is activated in these cells, leading to the synthesis and secretion of EPO.\r\n\r\nThe production of EPO by the kidneys is tightly regulated to maintain the appropriate oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. Conditions such as hypoxia, anemia, and renal disease can influence EPO production and lead to alterations in red blood cell production.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 414.","responses":[{"text":"Kidneys","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10022,"text":"Which of the following does not have a capsule?","explanation":"Peyer's patches are **lymphoid aggregates found in the intestinal mucosa** and they do not have a capsule. Peyer's patches are part of the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) and play a crucial role in the immune response to pathogens that enter the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nUnlike other lymphoid organs mentioned in the options, such as the spleen, lymph nodes, and palatine tonsils, which have a well-defined capsule surrounding their structure, Peyer's patches lack a distinct capsule. Instead, they are composed of lymphoid follicles containing B and T lymphocytes, as well as specialized epithelial cells called M cells.\r\n\r\nM cells in the Peyer's patches function to sample antigens from the gut lumen and deliver them to underlying lymphoid cells for immune surveillance and response. This unique feature allows Peyer's patches to play a significant role in mucosal immunity.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Palatine tonsils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peyer's patches","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph node","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10023,"text":"After a long bone fracture, when is a fat embolism likely to occur?","explanation":"A **fat embolism** is most likely to occur **1-3 days** after a long bone fracture. Fat embolism syndrome (FES) is a rare but potentially serious condition characterized by the release of fat globules into the bloodstream. In the context of a long bone fracture, the fracture disrupts the medullary canal, allowing fat from the bone marrow to enter the circulation.\r\n\r\nWithin the first 24 hours after a fracture, patients may experience symptoms related to the fracture itself, such as pain and swelling. However, the onset of fat embolism syndrome typically occurs after this initial period. The fat globules released from the bone marrow can travel through the bloodstream and become lodged in small blood vessels, leading to organ dysfunction.\r\n\r\nThe classic triad of symptoms associated with fat embolism syndrome includes respiratory distress, neurological abnormalities (such as confusion or coma), and petechial rash. Prompt recognition and supportive management are crucial in the management of FES.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 128.","responses":[{"text":"After 1 hour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"After 24 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"After 1-3 days","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"After 1 month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"After 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10024,"text":"A 34-year-old woman is evaluated at the hospital and found to have a large ovarian cyst. During surgery of the cysts, it is found to contain cheesy material, teeth, and hair. What is this type of cyst called?","explanation":"**Mature cystic teratomas**, also called dermoid cysts, are a common type of ovarian germ cell tumor characterized by the presence of multiple tissue types derived from all three germ layers: ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm.\r\n\r\nThese cysts typically contain a variety of well-differentiated tissues, including hair, teeth, sebaceous glands, and neural tissue. The presence of cheesy material, teeth, and hair within the cyst is characteristic of a mature cystic teratoma. The development of these structures within the cyst is due to the totipotential nature of germ cells, which have the ability to differentiate into various cell types.\r\n\r\nMature cystic teratomas are usually benign and are most commonly encountered in women of reproductive age. They are typically unilateral and can range in size from a few centimeters to large masses.","reference":"Mobeen S, Apostol R. Ovarian cyst. StatPearls. Published online May 1, 2022. Accessed June 7, 2022. https://www.statpearls.com/articlelibrary/viewarticle/26445/","responses":[{"text":"Mucinous cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystadenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chocolate cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mature cystic teratoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystadenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10025,"text":"A 60-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with complaints of burning micturition and fever. On examination, blood pressure is 90/60 mm of Hg, and heart rate is 110 beats/min. The physician also notices blood oozing from a cannulation site. A complete blood count shows low hemoglobin, high WBC count, and low platelet count. Further investigation reveals prolonged PT and aPTT. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)** is a complex disorder characterized by widespread activation of the coagulation system, leading to both excessive clotting and subsequent consumption of clotting factors and platelets. It can occur as a secondary complication of various underlying conditions, such as severe infections, sepsis, malignancies, trauma, and obstetric complications.\r\n\r\nThe patient's symptoms of burning micturition and fever, along with the findings of low blood pressure, tachycardia, and bleeding from the cannulation site, indicate a systemic inflammatory response. The laboratory results of low hemoglobin, high white blood cell count, low platelet count, and prolonged PT and aPTT support the diagnosis of DIC.\r\n\r\nIn DIC, the activation of the coagulation system leads to the consumption of clotting factors and platelets, resulting in decreased levels of these factors and prolonged clotting times. The increased fibrinolysis in DIC further contributes to the bleeding tendency observed in this patient.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 664-665.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 435.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic autoimmune thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disseminated intravascular coagulation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10026,"text":"In case of an injury, a deficiency of which of the following would impair the adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen?","explanation":"In the process of hemostasis, adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen is a crucial step in forming a platelet plug to prevent bleeding. The key molecule involved in this adhesion is **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand factor is a multimeric glycoprotein synthesized by endothelial cells and megakaryocytes. It plays a critical role in mediating platelet adhesion by binding to both the exposed collagen at the site of injury and the platelet surface receptor, glycoprotein Ib (GPIb). This interaction between vWF and GPIb allows platelets to adhere to the damaged vessel wall and initiate the formation of a platelet plug.\r\n\r\nDeficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor can lead to a bleeding disorder known as von Willebrand disease, characterized by impaired platelet adhesion and defective clot formation. Without adequate von Willebrand factor, platelets are unable to adhere effectively to the subendothelial collagen, resulting in impaired hemostasis and prolonged bleeding.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen stabilizing factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand factor","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10027,"text":"If there is a defect of the mesoderm, which cells are primarily affected?","explanation":"The thymus is derived from the third pharyngeal pouch, which is a structure formed from the endoderm and mesoderm. The thymus is responsible for the maturation and differentiation of thymocytes, which are precursors of T lymphocytes.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, **thymocytes** migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they undergo a process of education and selection, leading to the development of functional T cells. The mesoderm provides the essential structural support and signaling molecules necessary for the proper development and function of the thymus.\r\n\r\nA defect in the mesoderm can disrupt the normal development of the thymus, leading to impaired maturation and differentiation of thymocytes. This can result in immunodeficiency and compromised immune function.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 47.","responses":[{"text":"Nurse cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymic epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10028,"text":"Which of the following is formed by complement activation?","explanation":"Complement activation is a key component of the immune response and plays a crucial role in host defense against pathogens. One of the major outcomes of complement activation is the formation of the **membrane attack complex (MAC)**.\r\n\r\nThe MAC is a complex structure composed of complement proteins that assemble on the surface of target cells, such as bacteria or infected cells. It forms a pore-like structure in the cell membrane, leading to cell lysis and destruction. The MAC aids in the elimination of pathogens and infected cells by disrupting their integrity and causing their destruction.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"Membrane attack complex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10029,"text":"A patient was given a few milliliters of blood after which he developed an immediate reaction consisting of fever, hypotension, tachypnea, and tachycardia. Which of the following is true about this kind of reaction?","explanation":"The immediate reaction observed in the patient after receiving blood is suggestive of an **acute hemolytic transfusion reaction**. This type of reaction occurs when the recipient's antibodies, specifically IgM and IgG, attack the donor red blood cells (RBCs). The antibodies recognize antigens on the surface of the donor RBCs as foreign and initiate an immune response.\r\n\r\nWhen incompatible blood is transfused, the recipient's antibodies bind to the donor RBCs, leading to their destruction through a process called hemolysis. This hemolysis releases hemoglobin into the bloodstream, resulting in various systemic manifestations, including fever, hypotension, tachypnea, and tachycardia.\r\n\r\nThe reaction occurs due to **host antibodies attacking donor cells**, leading to the destruction of the transfused RBCs. This type of immune-mediated response can be severe and life-threatening, necessitating immediate medical intervention.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 671.","responses":[{"text":"Host cells and donor complement proteins react","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Donor cells and host complement proteins react","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Donor antibodies attack host cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The reaction is due to preformed IgE granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Host antibodies attack donor cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10051,"text":"The receptor for IgG is present on phagocytes. Which of the following are phagocytes?","explanation":"Phagocytes are immune cells that are specialized in engulfing and destroying foreign particles, such as bacteria and cellular debris. They play a crucial role in the immune response by eliminating pathogens and initiating inflammatory responses. **Macrophages and neutrophils** are examples of phagocytes.\r\n\r\nMacrophages are large, highly versatile immune cells found in various tissues throughout the body. They are involved in both innate and adaptive immune responses. Macrophages express receptors for IgG antibodies, allowing them to recognize and bind to pathogens opsonized with IgG. This facilitates the phagocytosis of the pathogens and their subsequent destruction.\r\n\r\nNeutrophils are the most abundant type of white blood cells and are essential for the early defense against bacterial infections. They are highly efficient phagocytes and express receptors for IgG antibodies, which enhance their ability to recognize and engulf opsonized pathogens.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 451.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages and lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophage and neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10054,"text":"Which of the following is not an example of an antibody-mediated response?","explanation":"**Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)** is an immune reaction that occurs when immunocompetent cells from a graft (such as bone marrow or stem cells) recognize the recipient's tissues as foreign and mount an attack. In GVHD, the donor T cells attack the recipient's tissues, leading to tissue damage and inflammation. This immune response is primarily cell-mediated and involves the activation of T cells, rather than the production of antibodies by B cells.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, **drug-induced hemolytic anemia, blood transfusion reactions, Rh incompatibility at birth, and autoimmune diseases** are examples of antibody-mediated responses. These conditions involve the production of antibodies by B cells that recognize and target specific antigens, leading to tissue damage, destruction of red blood cells, or inflammation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Graft-versus-host disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood transfusion reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug-induced hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rh incompatibility at birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10056,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding individuals with blood group A?","explanation":"Individuals with blood group A have **anti-B antibodies in their plasma**, which means their immune system recognizes the B antigen as foreign. This is due to the presence of A antigens on their red blood cells (RBCs) and the absence of B antigens. The anti-B antibodies in their plasma can agglutinate and cause hemolysis of RBCs with B antigens if transfused with incompatible blood.\r\n\r\nThese individuals can **give blood for transfusion to persons of blood group A and AB** because both groups have A antigens on their RBCs, which are compatible with anti-A antibodies that may be present in the donor's plasma. However, they should avoid donating blood to individuals with blood group B or AB, as their plasma contains anti-B antibodies that can cause an immune response.\r\n\r\nIn terms of offspring, individuals with blood group A can have children with blood groups A and O. This is because individuals with blood group A may carry two copies of the A allele (genotype AA) or one A allele and one O allele (genotype AO).","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 413.","responses":[{"text":"They may give blood for transfusion to person of blood group O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They may have phenotype AB","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They may have children with blood group A and O only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have B antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have anti-B antibodies in their plasma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10074,"text":"A 13-year-old girl falls and hits her head on the wall, leading to trauma of the blood vessels. Tissue thromboplastin will be released by the endothelial cells. Which of the following factors will be involved in initiating coagulation?","explanation":"When tissue thromboplastin is exposed to circulating **Factor VII**, it binds to the tissue factor and forms a complex. This complex, along with calcium ions, activates Factor X to its active form, Factor Xa. Factor Xa then acts as a catalyst in the common pathway of coagulation, leading to the formation of a fibrin clot.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the intrinsic pathway is not involved in this initial phase of coagulation following trauma. Factors IX, XII, and HMWK are part of the intrinsic pathway, which is primarily activated by contact with negatively charged surfaces. In this case, the trauma to the blood vessels triggers the extrinsic pathway.\r\n\r\nReference: Hall JE, Guyton AC. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th edition. Elsevier, 2021.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 481.","responses":[{"text":"High-molecular-weight kininogen (HMWK)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10075,"text":"What are plasma cells derived from?","explanation":"**Plasma cells** are derived from **B lymphocytes**. B lymphocytes are a type of white blood cell involved in the adaptive immune response. They originate from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow and undergo maturation and differentiation processes to become mature B cells.\r\n\r\nWhen an antigen enters the body and interacts with a specific B cell receptor (BCR) on the surface of a mature B cell, the B cell is activated. The activated B cell undergoes clonal expansion and differentiation into two main cell types: memory B cells and plasma cells.\r\n\r\nPlasma cells are the effector cells of the humoral immune response. They are responsible for producing and secreting large amounts of **antibodies** (also known as immunoglobulins) that can recognize and bind to specific antigens. The process of differentiation from activated B cell to plasma cell involves changes in gene expression and the development of specialized machinery for antibody synthesis and secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 462-463.","responses":[{"text":"Megakaryocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B lymphocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10076,"text":"Which of the following is not an antibody-mediated disease?","explanation":"**Hemophilia** is not an antibody-mediated disease. Hemophilia is a **genetic disorder** characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of clotting factors, specifically **factor VIII (hemophilia A) or factor IX (hemophilia B)**. It is not caused by antibodies targeting specific antigens. In hemophilia, the clotting process is impaired, leading to prolonged bleeding and difficulty in forming blood clots. Antibody-mediated diseases involve an immune response where antibodies are produced and target specific antigens, leading to tissue damage or dysfunction. Examples of antibody-mediated diseases include hemolytic anemia, urticaria (hives), and immune thrombocytopenia (ITP). Asthma, on the other hand, is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways and is not primarily antibody-mediated, although it does involve immune system activation.","reference":"Justiz Vaillant AA, Vashisht R, Zito PM. Immediate hypersensitivity reactions. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513315/","responses":[{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenia (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urticaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10077,"text":"Which of the following lymphatic tissues is characterized by the presence of subcapsular sinus?","explanation":"The lymph node is characterized by the presence of a **subcapsular sinus**, making it the correct answer. Lymph nodes are important secondary lymphoid organs involved in the immune response. They contain various regions, including the cortex and medulla, which are separated by a boundary called the corticomedullary junction.\r\n\r\nThe subcapsular sinus is a space located beneath the capsule of the lymph node. It is lined by specialized endothelial cells and serves as the initial site of antigen capture and immune cell activation. Lymph fluid and antigens enter the subcapsular sinus, where they encounter antigen-presenting cells such as dendritic cells. These cells capture and process antigens, initiating an immune response within the lymph node.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tonsil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peyer's patch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph node","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10078,"text":"Which model of disease causation is used when agent, host, and environment are considered?","explanation":"The **epidemiological triad** model is used when agent, host, and environment are considered in disease causation. This model recognizes that the occurrence and development of disease result from the complex interaction of these three components. \r\n\r\n1. **Agent**: The agent refers to the infectious organism or factor that causes the disease. It can be a microorganism, such as a bacteria or virus, or a non-infectious agent, such as a chemical or physical factor.\r\n\r\n2. **Host**: The host is the individual or population that is susceptible to the disease. Factors such as age, gender, genetic predisposition, and immune status can influence an individual's susceptibility to a particular disease.\r\n\r\n3. **Environment**: The environment encompasses the external factors that surround the host and interact with the agent. This includes physical, biological, social, and cultural factors that can influence the transmission and development of the disease.\r\n\r\nUnderstanding the interactions among the agent, host, and environment is crucial for identifying risk factors, implementing preventive measures, and designing effective interventions to control and prevent disease.","reference":"1. 2 - epidemiologic triad | stat 507. PennState: Statistics Online Courses. Accessed June 11, 2022. https://online.stat.psu.edu/stat507/lesson/1/1.2","responses":[{"text":"Population pyramid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wheel model","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Web of causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiological triad","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10092,"text":"Which of the following components are involved in the first step of heme synthesis?","explanation":"The synthesis of heme, a vital molecule for the formation of hemoglobin, begins with the condensation of **succinyl CoA and glycine**. This reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme aminolevulinic acid synthase (ALAS). The resulting product, aminolevulinic acid (ALA), is a key intermediate in the heme synthesis pathway.\r\n\r\nALAS is the rate-limiting enzyme in heme synthesis and its activity is regulated by various factors, including the availability of succinyl CoA and glycine. Succinyl CoA is derived from the citric acid cycle, while glycine is an amino acid. Together, they provide the building blocks for the initial step of heme synthesis.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 278\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 235","responses":[{"text":"Succinyl CoA and serine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malonyl CoA and glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA and glycine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malonyl CoA and serine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10095,"text":"Which antibody acts as a B cell antigen receptor and plays a role in B cell maturation, maintenance, silencing, and activation?","explanation":"**IgM** is the first immunoglobulin produced by B cells during an immune response and acts as a B cell antigen receptor. It plays a critical role in B cell maturation, maintenance, silencing, and activation. IgM is present on the surface of naive B cells as a monomer and is also secreted as a pentamer. As a B cell receptor, IgM interacts with antigens and initiates the activation of B cells, leading to their proliferation and differentiation into antibody-secreting plasma cells. IgM is particularly effective in activating the complement system, which enhances the immune response against pathogens. Additionally, IgM is involved in the primary immune response, while other antibody classes such as IgG and IgA are more prominent in the secondary immune response.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 534.","responses":[{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10110,"text":"Which type of cancer is the squamous cell carcinoma of the lungs?","explanation":"Squamous cell carcinoma of the lungs is a **malignant tumor of epithelium**. It arises from the **squamous epithelial cells** lining the respiratory bronchi, bronchioles, and alveoli.\r\n\r\nThe development of squamous cell carcinoma is strongly associated with **tobacco smoking**. Prolonged exposure to carcinogens in tobacco smoke leads to genetic mutations and molecular alterations in the bronchial epithelium, promoting the transformation of normal cells into malignant squamous cells.\r\n\r\nHistologically, squamous cell carcinoma is characterized by the presence of atypical squamous cells with **keratinization** and **intercellular bridges**. These malignant cells invade the surrounding lung tissue, leading to the destruction of normal lung architecture and potential metastasis to regional lymph nodes and distant sites.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 269.","responses":[{"text":"Benign tumor of epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant tumor of mesenchyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant tumor of epithelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign tumor of mesenchyme","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10112,"text":"Which of the following is used to detect hereditary spherocytosis?","explanation":"To detect **hereditary spherocytosis**, an inherited disorder characterized by the presence of spherocytic red blood cells, the **osmotic fragility test** is commonly used. This test measures the ability of red blood cells to withstand osmotic stress and hemolysis.\r\n\r\nIn hereditary spherocytosis, the red blood cells have a decreased ability to withstand changes in osmotic pressure due to defects in the membrane proteins involved in maintaining cell shape and stability. As a result, these cells become more fragile and prone to hemolysis.\r\n\r\nThe osmotic fragility test involves subjecting red blood cells to a range of varying osmotic pressures. The degree of hemolysis is then assessed, and the osmotic fragility curve is plotted. In hereditary spherocytosis, the curve is shifted to the left, indicating increased fragility and earlier hemolysis compared to normal red blood cells.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 47.","responses":[{"text":"Serum B12 levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osmotic fragility test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MCHC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MCV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RBC count","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10113,"text":"Which of the following is the first clotting factor that is common in both extrinsic and intrinsic pathway?","explanation":"The first clotting factor that is common to both the extrinsic and intrinsic pathways of coagulation is **Factor X**, also known as Stuart-Prower factor. Factor X is an important enzyme that plays a key role in the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin, which is a critical step in the clotting process.\r\n\r\nThe extrinsic pathway is initiated by the release of tissue factor (Factor III) from damaged endothelial cells or extravascular tissues. Tissue factor combines with Factor VII to form an activated complex that activates Factor X. On the other hand, the intrinsic pathway is triggered by activation of Factor XII by contact with exposed subendothelial components. The activated Factor XII then leads to the sequential activation of other factors, including Factor XI, Factor IX, and Factor VIII, ultimately leading to the activation of Factor X.\r\n\r\nOnce Factor X is activated, it converges with the common pathway of coagulation, leading to the formation of a fibrin clot.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 487-488.","responses":[{"text":"Factor II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10114,"text":"Hemophilia A is characterized by the deficiency of which factors?","explanation":"Hemophilia A is characterized by the deficiency of **Factor VIII**, also known as antihemophilic factor. Factor VIII is an essential clotting factor involved in the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade. Its deficiency leads to impaired blood clotting and a tendency to bleed excessively.\r\n\r\nHemophilia A is an X-linked recessive disorder, predominantly affecting males. The severity of the condition depends on the extent of Factor VIII deficiency. Individuals with severe hemophilia A have very low levels of Factor VIII and experience frequent spontaneous bleeding episodes, while those with mild or moderate hemophilia A may have milder symptoms and bleeding tendencies triggered by trauma or surgery.\r\n\r\nThe diagnosis of hemophilia A is confirmed by measuring Factor VIII activity levels in the blood. Treatment involves replacement therapy with recombinant or plasma-derived Factor VIII to restore normal clotting function and prevent or manage bleeding episodes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 668.","responses":[{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10115,"text":"Which of the following is an indication for prenatal diagnostic tests?","explanation":"**Prenatal diagnostic tests** are performed during pregnancy to detect any abnormalities or genetic disorders in the developing fetus. They are usually recommended for women with specific risk factors or indications. One such indication is a **past history of neural tube defects**. Neural tube defects are serious congenital malformations of the brain and spinal cord, and a previous occurrence in the family increases the risk of recurrence in subsequent pregnancies. Prenatal diagnostic tests can help identify these defects early in pregnancy, allowing for appropriate management and counseling.\r\n\r\nOther common indications for prenatal diagnostic tests include advanced maternal age (typically 35 years or older), family history of genetic disorders, abnormal ultrasound findings, and certain maternal medical conditions. These tests help in assessing the health and well-being of the fetus and enable informed decision-making regarding further management.","reference":"Prenatal diagnosis and prenatal screening—methods and tests. The Lecturio Online Medical Library. Published August 25, 2017. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.lecturio.com/magazine/prenatal-diagnosis-prenatal-screening/","responses":[{"text":"Mother taking no medication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history of cigarette smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Past history of neural tube defects","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maternal age \u003c 15 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maternal age \u003c 30 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10116,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding the histology of the spleen?","explanation":"The **periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths (PALS)** are a part of the white pulp in the spleen and surround the central arteries. They consist primarily of T lymphocytes and are involved in the immune response. **Neutrophils, on the other hand, are not typically found in the PALS** but are more commonly associated with the innate immune response.\r\n\r\nThe spleen is composed of two main regions: the white pulp and the red pulp. The white pulp contains lymphoid tissue, including the PALS, where immune responses are initiated. The red pulp consists of splenic sinusoids, cords of Billroth, and splenic sinuses, which are involved in filtering and removing aged or damaged blood cells.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 286, 290.\r\n\r\n(2) Characterization and Isolation of Splenic Littoral Cells, a Possible Cellular Niche for Extramedullary Hematopoiesis in Myelofibrosis\r\nAccessed June 12, 2022. https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/126/23/3594/92919/Characterization-and-Isolation-of-Splenic-Littoral","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils are the predominant cells of the periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths (PALS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"White pulp contains leukocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Littoral cells are found in splenic sinusoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red pulp contains sinusoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The spleen contains cords of Billroth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10117,"text":"Which of the following results from the deficiency of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase?","explanation":"The deficiency of **uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase** leads to **Porphyria cutanea tarda**. Porphyrias are a group of inherited disorders characterized by defects in heme synthesis, resulting in the accumulation of porphyrins or their precursors.\r\n\r\nPorphyria cutanea tarda (PCT) is the most common form of porphyria and is caused by a deficiency of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase, an enzyme involved in the conversion of uroporphyrinogen III to coproporphyrinogen III. The deficiency of this enzyme leads to the accumulation of uroporphyrinogen and its subsequent conversion into uroporphyrins, which are photosensitive compounds.\r\n\r\nThe accumulation of uroporphyrins in the skin makes individuals with PCT extremely sensitive to sunlight, resulting in photosensitivity reactions. This manifests as blistering, erosions, and skin fragility, particularly on sun-exposed areas such as the face and hands.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 281.","responses":[{"text":"Acute intermittent porphyria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hereditary coproporphyria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sideroblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variegate porphyria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Porphyria cutanea tarda","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10119,"text":"To slow down the coagulation process, thrombin binds to which of the following proteins?","explanation":"To slow down the coagulation process, thrombin binds to **thrombomodulin**. Thrombomodulin is a protein found on the surface of endothelial cells lining blood vessels. When thrombin binds to thrombomodulin, it undergoes a conformational change that switches its activity from a procoagulant to an anticoagulant.\r\n\r\nThe binding of thrombin to thrombomodulin activates the protein C pathway, which plays a crucial role in regulating coagulation. Thrombomodulin facilitates the activation of protein C by forming a complex with thrombin, resulting in the proteolytic cleavage and activation of protein C. Activated protein C then inhibits the clotting cascade by proteolytically inactivating factors Va and VIIIa, which are necessary for efficient clot formation.\r\n\r\nBy binding to thrombomodulin, thrombin is redirected from promoting clot formation to exerting anticoagulant effects through the activation of protein C.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Protein C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein S","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombomodulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10120,"text":"A first-year medical student has a fever and sore throat. The physician prescribes Ibuprofen. Which process is involved in relieving the pain and fever?","explanation":"The process involved in relieving pain and fever by **Ibuprofen** is the **reversible inhibition of cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes**, reducing prostaglandin production. Ibuprofen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that exerts its effects by inhibiting the activity of COX enzymes, specifically COX-1 and COX-2. These enzymes are responsible for the conversion of arachidonic acid into prostaglandins, which are mediators of pain, inflammation, and fever.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting COX enzymes, Ibuprofen reduces the production of prostaglandins, thereby decreasing pain and inflammation and lowering body temperature in cases of fever. The reversible nature of the inhibition allows the effects of Ibuprofen to be temporary, as the enzyme activity can be restored once the drug is eliminated from the body.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 512.","responses":[{"text":"It irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase, reducing prostaglandin production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It reversibly inhibits phospholipase A2, reducing arachidonic acid production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It reversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase, reducing prostaglandin production","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It irreversibly inhibits phospholipase A2, reducing arachidonic acid production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10122,"text":"A venous embolism is likely to cause an infarct in which of the following organs?","explanation":"A **venous embolism** is likely to cause an infarct in the **lung**. When a venous embolus, such as a blood clot or fat globule, becomes lodged in a pulmonary artery, it can block the blood supply to a portion of the lung tissue. This obstruction prevents adequate oxygenation and blood flow to the affected area, leading to ischemia and subsequent infarction.\r\n\r\nThe lung is particularly susceptible to venous embolisms due to its extensive vascular network. Pulmonary embolisms commonly arise from deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the lower extremities, where a clot dislodges and travels to the lung via the venous system.\r\n\r\nThe other organs mentioned may be more susceptible to arterial embolisms. Arterial embolisms occur when an embolus obstructs an artery, cutting off the blood supply to the organ downstream. However, venous emboli are less likely to cause infarction in these organs due to alternative blood supply routes or collateral circulation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Alll of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10126,"text":"What is the sudden occurrence of cases in a relatively larger geographical area with more than one focal point known as?","explanation":"The sudden occurrence of cases in a relatively larger geographical area with more than one focal point is known as an **epidemic**. An epidemic refers to the rapid spread of a disease or condition within a population, surpassing the expected number of cases. It indicates a higher incidence of the disease compared to the usual or expected level.\r\n\r\nDuring an epidemic, the disease may affect multiple communities or regions simultaneously, and there is a noticeable increase in the number of cases. The term \"epidemic\" is commonly used to describe the occurrence of infectious diseases, such as influenza, measles, or dengue fever, but it can also be applied to non-infectious conditions that exhibit a similar pattern of rapid and widespread occurrence.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, an **outbreak** typically refers to a sudden increase in the number of cases within a localized area or community. **Endemic** refers to the constant presence of a disease within a specific geographic area. **Pandemic** refers to a global epidemic, affecting multiple countries or continents.","reference":"Principles of epidemiology: glossary. Published December 20, 2021. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/glossary.html","responses":[{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Outbreak","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10128,"text":"Which of the following lymphoid organs has stratified squamous epithelial lining?","explanation":"The **palatine tonsils** are the lymphoid organs that have a **stratified squamous epithelial lining**. They are located on either side of the oropharynx, between the palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches. The tonsils are part of the Waldeyer's ring, which is a collection of lymphoid tissues in the oral and pharyngeal region.\r\n\r\nThe stratified squamous epithelium of the palatine tonsils serves as a protective barrier against pathogens entering through the oral cavity. It contains invaginations called tonsillar crypts, which increase the surface area for antigen exposure and facilitate the capture of antigens by immune cells.\r\n\r\nLymph nodes have a reticular epithelial lining. The thymus has an epithelial lining composed of thymic epithelial cells. The spleen does not have a stratified squamous epithelial lining; instead, it has a specialized reticular endothelial lining.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatine tonsil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10130,"text":"Which of the following factors is deficient in hemophilia B?","explanation":"**Hemophilia B**, also known as Christmas disease, is a hereditary bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency or dysfunction of coagulation **factor IX**. It is an X-linked recessive disorder, predominantly affecting males.\r\n\r\nFactor IX is a clotting factor that plays a crucial role in the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade. In hemophilia B, the deficiency of factor IX leads to impaired blood clotting and prolonged bleeding. The severity of symptoms can vary, with individuals experiencing recurrent episodes of spontaneous bleeding, particularly in joints and muscles.\r\n\r\nFactor VIII deficiency is associated with hemophilia A, which is the most common form of hemophilia. Factor X deficiency leads to a rare bleeding disorder called Stuart-Prower disease. Factor VII deficiency results in another rare bleeding disorder known as factor VII deficiency or Alexander's disease. Tissue factor is not a factor deficiency but rather a protein involved in initiating the extrinsic pathway of coagulation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 669.","responses":[{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue factor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10132,"text":"Which of the following leads to a decrease in plasma oncotic pressure?","explanation":"Plasma oncotic pressure, also known as colloid osmotic pressure, is primarily determined by the concentration of plasma proteins, especially albumin. Albumin is the main protein responsible for maintaining oncotic pressure in the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nWhen there is a **decrease in the concentration of plasma albumin**, such as in conditions like liver disease or malnutrition, the plasma oncotic pressure decreases. This reduction in oncotic pressure disrupts the balance between the intravascular and extravascular compartments, leading to a shift of fluid from the intravascular space to the interstitial space.\r\n\r\nInflammation and lymphatic obstruction can lead to an increase in interstitial fluid volume but do not directly cause a decrease in plasma oncotic pressure. Hyperproteinemia, an increase in plasma protein levels, would actually increase the plasma oncotic pressure rather than decrease it.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 199.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphatic obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperproteinemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma albumin decrement","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10135,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding hereditary spherocytosis?","explanation":"**Hereditary spherocytosis** is an inherited disorder characterized by the presence of spherocytes, which are spherical-shaped red blood cells lacking the central pallor. The correct answer is that hereditary spherocytosis is associated with **increased osmotic fragility** of the red blood cells.\r\n\r\nIn hereditary spherocytosis, there is a defect in the red blood cell membrane, specifically in the proteins involved in maintaining the biconcave shape of the cells. This defect leads to the formation of spherical-shaped red blood cells that are more prone to destruction in the spleen due to their altered membrane properties.\r\n\r\nThe increased osmotic fragility refers to the increased vulnerability of the red blood cells to rupture when exposed to hypotonic solutions. This is a characteristic feature of hereditary spherocytosis and can be used as a diagnostic test.\r\n\r\nThe other options mentioned are incorrect. Spherocytes in hereditary spherocytosis have decreased central pallor, not increased. High mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and low mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration (MCHC) are not specific findings in hereditary spherocytosis.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 47.","responses":[{"text":"Spherocytes with increased central pallor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased osmotic fragility","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low MCHC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High MCV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10137,"text":"In the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve, a decrease in pH will lead to which of the following?","explanation":"A **decrease in pH** will lead to a *curve shift to the right* in the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve. This shift is known as the **Bohr effect**. \r\n\r\nThe Bohr effect describes the phenomenon where a decrease in pH, resulting from an increase in carbon dioxide (CO2) levels or a decrease in blood pH, decreases the affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen. This means that hemoglobin will release oxygen more readily to the tissues.\r\n\r\nThe decrease in pH causes hemoglobin to undergo a conformational change that reduces its affinity for oxygen, allowing for more efficient oxygen unloading in tissues with high metabolic demands. This shift to the right in the dissociation curve indicates a lower affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen at a given partial pressure of oxygen (PO2).\r\n\r\nThe other options mentioned are incorrect. A decrease in pH does not affect the affinity of hemoglobin to CO2. It specifically affects the oxygen binding capacity and oxygen release of hemoglobin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 31.","responses":[{"text":"Increased affinity of hemoglobin to CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No change","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased affinity of hemoglobin to CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Curve shift to the left","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Curve shift to the right","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10139,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding the factors affecting the affinity of hemoglobin for O2?","explanation":"*2,3-BPG* is a molecule produced during glycolysis and is present in red blood cells. It binds to hemoglobin and reduces its affinity for oxygen.\r\n\r\nWhen 2,3-BPG levels are elevated, such as in conditions of low oxygen levels or high altitude, it binds to hemoglobin and promotes the release of oxygen to the tissues. This phenomenon is known as the Bohr effect. Conversely, when 2,3-BPG levels are decreased, hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen increases, favoring oxygen uptake in the lungs.\r\n\r\nThe affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen decreases with an increase in CO2, increases with an increase in temperature, and decreases with a decrease in pH (Bohr effect). The statement that the affinity increases with an increase in pH is incorrect.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 31.","responses":[{"text":"Increases with decrease in pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases with increase in 2,3-BPG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases with increase in CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases with increase in temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases with increase in pH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10141,"text":"Congenital deficiency of a specific protein leads to the inability to transport conjugated bilirubin out of the liver and into the bile. This statement is most relevant for which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Dubin-Johnson syndrome** is a rare autosomal recessive disorder characterized by impaired hepatic excretion of conjugated bilirubin into the bile. It is caused by a deficiency or dysfunction of a specific protein called multidrug resistance-associated protein 2 (MRP2), which is responsible for transporting conjugated bilirubin from hepatocytes into the bile canaliculi.\r\n\r\nAs a result of MRP2 deficiency, conjugated bilirubin accumulates within the hepatocytes, leading to elevated levels of conjugated bilirubin in the blood. This results in a characteristic clinical manifestation of persistent or intermittent jaundice, where the skin and sclerae appear yellowish.\r\n\r\nOther conditions mentioned in the options are not directly associated with impaired bilirubin transport. Crigler-Najjar syndrome is caused by a deficiency of the enzyme responsible for conjugating bilirubin, obstructive jaundice is typically caused by a physical obstruction of the bile ducts, physiologic jaundice of the newborn is a normal transient condition, and Gilbert syndrome is characterized by a decreased activity of the enzyme responsible for conjugating bilirubin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 283.","responses":[{"text":"Crigler-Najjar syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gilbert syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiologic jaundice of the newborn","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dubin-Johnson syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10142,"text":"Blood is a special type of connective tissue. Which of the following is correct regarding it?","explanation":"Blood is indeed a special type of connective tissue, and one of the key characteristics that sets it apart is the nature of its ground substance. The ground substance of blood is of a fluid nature, known as plasma. Plasma is a clear, yellowish liquid that forms the matrix of blood. It contains water, proteins, electrolytes, hormones, gases, nutrients, and waste products. The fluid nature of the ground substance allows blood to flow freely through the circulatory system and carry out its vital functions.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the fluid ground substance, blood also contains cells and fibers. The cellular component of blood includes red blood cells (erythrocytes), white blood cells (leukocytes), and platelets (thrombocytes). These cells play important roles in oxygen transport, immune response, and blood clotting. The fibers found in blood are primarily fibrin, which forms a meshwork during clotting to help stop bleeding.\r\n\r\nWhile blood does contain fibers, its ground substance is primarily fluid in nature, distinguishing it from other connective tissues that have a more solid or gel-like ground substance.","reference":"Is blood a connective tissue? - woms. Published September 19, 2021. Accessed June 12, 2022. //worldofmedicalsaviours.com/is-blood-a-connective-tissue/","responses":[{"text":"It contains fibers only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It contains both cells and fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a greater proportion of cells as compared to fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Its ground substance is of a fluid nature","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10143,"text":"Which antibody is found in the respiratory and digestive lining, as well as the saliva, tears, and breast milk?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 105.","responses":[{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10144,"text":"Which antibody crosses the placenta during erythroblastosis fetalis?","explanation":"During erythroblastosis fetalis, which is an immune-mediated condition where maternal antibodies attack fetal red blood cells, the antibody that crosses the placenta and plays a significant role in the pathogenesis is **IgG**. \r\n\r\nIgG is the only antibody class capable of crossing the placenta due to its small size and unique structure. It is actively transported across the placental barrier from the mother to the fetus through specialized transport proteins called FcRn receptors. This transplacental transfer of IgG provides passive immunity to the fetus, offering protection against various infectious agents that the mother has encountered.\r\n\r\nIn the context of erythroblastosis fetalis, when the mother is Rh-negative and the fetus is Rh-positive, maternal IgG antibodies against the Rh antigen can cross the placenta and enter the fetal circulation. These antibodies target and destroy the fetal red blood cells, leading to hemolysis and subsequent complications.\r\n\r\nThe ability of IgG to cross the placenta and mediate immune responses in the fetus is an essential mechanism for protecting the newborn from infections and providing temporary immunity until the infant can develop its own immune system.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 523.","responses":[{"text":"IgG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10145,"text":"Which antibody is dimeric with a J chain?","explanation":"Among the different classes of antibodies (immunoglobulins), **IgA** is the antibody that exists as a dimer with a J (joining) chain. IgA plays a crucial role in mucosal immunity, protecting the body's mucosal surfaces such as the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and genitourinary tracts.\r\n\r\nThe dimeric structure of IgA consists of two monomeric subunits joined together by a J chain. Additionally, IgA can further be associated with a secretory component that is produced by epithelial cells, forming secretory IgA (sIgA). The secretory component helps protect IgA from degradation and facilitates its transport across mucosal surfaces.\r\n\r\nIgA is particularly important in providing immune defense against pathogens at mucosal surfaces. It acts by neutralizing and preventing the attachment of pathogens to epithelial cells, inhibiting their colonization and entry into the body.\r\n\r\nThe dimeric structure and association with the J chain and secretory component allow IgA to function effectively in mucosal immunity, providing a first line of defense against invading pathogens.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 525.","responses":[{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10146,"text":"Which antibody has a pentameric structure?","explanation":"Among the different classes of antibodies (immunoglobulins), **IgM** is the antibody that has a pentameric structure. IgM is the first antibody produced during the primary immune response and plays a crucial role in the early stages of an infection.\r\n\r\nThe pentameric structure of IgM consists of five monomeric subunits joined together by a J (joining) chain and disulfide bonds. This unique structure allows IgM to have multiple antigen-binding sites, enhancing its ability to bind to pathogens and facilitate their removal from the body.\r\n\r\nThe large size and pentameric structure of IgM contribute to its efficient functioning in the immune response. It enables IgM to effectively agglutinate (clump together) antigens, activate complement system components, and facilitate phagocytosis by macrophages.\r\n\r\nWhile other antibody classes, such as IgG, IgA, IgD, and IgE, exist as monomers or dimers, IgM stands out for its pentameric structure, making it highly effective in the early stages of immune defense.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 103.","responses":[{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10147,"text":"Which antibody isotype is the most abundant in serum?","explanation":"Among the various antibody isotypes, **IgG** is the **most abundant** in serum. **IgG antibodies** make up approximately 75-80% of the total immunoglobulin pool in the bloodstream. \r\n\r\nIgG is produced by plasma cells and is involved in several immune functions, including neutralization of pathogens, opsonization (enhancing phagocytosis), activation of complement system, and providing passive immunity to the fetus during pregnancy.\r\n\r\nIgM, on the other hand, is the first antibody produced during the primary immune response. It is a pentameric antibody and is present primarily in the early stages of an infection. IgM constitutes about 5-10% of the total serum immunoglobulins.\r\n\r\nIgD is primarily found on the surface of mature B cells and is involved in the activation of these cells. It is present in very low concentrations in serum.\r\n\r\nIgA is the predominant antibody isotype in mucosal secretions, such as saliva, tears, and respiratory and gastrointestinal tract secretions. It plays a crucial role in mucosal immunity and defense against pathogens at mucosal surfaces.\r\n\r\nIgE is involved in allergic reactions and defense against parasitic infections. It is present in very low concentrations in serum.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 270.","responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10149,"text":"Which of the following may result from frequent blood transfusions?","explanation":"**Frequent blood transfusions** can lead to an excess accumulation of iron in the body, a condition known as **hemochromatosis**. Blood transfusions provide additional iron that exceeds the body's normal capacity for iron storage and utilization. As a result, iron can accumulate in various organs and tissues, leading to damage and dysfunction.\r\n\r\nHemochromatosis is a genetic disorder characterized by increased absorption and accumulation of iron in the body. It can be primary (hereditary) or secondary (acquired). Frequent blood transfusions, particularly in conditions such as thalassemia, sickle cell disease, or myelodysplastic syndromes, can cause **secondary hemochromatosis**.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, anemia of chronic disease is a type of anemia that can occur in chronic inflammatory or autoimmune conditions, and it is characterized by decreased production of red blood cells. Iron deficiency anemia results from insufficient iron stores in the body. Wilson disease is a genetic disorder characterized by impaired copper metabolism.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 121.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wilson disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemochromatosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10150,"text":"Which type of hemoglobin prevents symptoms of thalassemia from appearing in neonatal life?","explanation":"The type of hemoglobin that prevents symptoms of thalassemia from appearing in neonatal life is **HbF (fetal hemoglobin)**.\r\n\r\nDuring fetal development, the production of HbF is predominant. **HbF** consists of two **alpha chains** and two **gamma chains**. This type of hemoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen than adult hemoglobin (HbA). The higher affinity of HbF for oxygen allows it to effectively acquire oxygen from the maternal circulation in the placenta and deliver it to the developing fetus.\r\n\r\nIn individuals with certain types of thalassemia, there is a deficiency in the production of one or more of the globin chains that make up adult hemoglobin (HbA). However, the production of HbF is not affected by these mutations. The presence of HbF helps to compensate for the reduced or abnormal production of adult hemoglobin, and it prevents the severe symptoms of thalassemia from appearing in the neonatal period.\r\n\r\nAs the neonate grows, the production of HbF gradually decreases, and the production of HbA increases. By around 6 months of age, the production of HbA becomes the predominant form of hemoglobin.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 44.","responses":[{"text":"HbC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbF","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11712,"text":"Which protein plays a major role in maintaining oncotic pressure and transportation of lipids and steroids?","explanation":"The protein that plays a major role in **maintaining oncotic pressure** and **transportation of lipids and steroids** is albumin.\r\n\r\n**Albumin** is the most abundant protein in the blood plasma and is synthesized by the liver. It contributes significantly to the osmotic pressure, also known as oncotic pressure, in the blood vessels. This pressure helps to retain fluid within the blood vessels and prevent its leakage into the surrounding tissues.\r\n\r\nAlbumin also acts as a carrier protein, transporting various substances in the blood, including fatty acids, bilirubin, hormones (such as steroids), and drugs. It binds to these molecules and helps transport them throughout the body.\r\n\r\nIn addition to its role in maintaining oncotic pressure and transportation, albumin also plays a part in regulating pH, buffering, and binding and transporting other substances like calcium and copper.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 181, 369.","responses":[{"text":"C-reactive protein (CRP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11713,"text":"How many oxygen molecules bind to a single hemoglobin molecule?","explanation":"Hemoglobin is composed of **four protein subunits**, each containing a **heme group**. Each heme group can bind one oxygen molecule. Since hemoglobin has four heme groups, it can bind up to **four oxygen molecules in total**.\r\n\r\nWhen all four heme groups in hemoglobin are bound to oxygen, the hemoglobin molecule is fully saturated, and it is in the **R state (relaxed state)**, which has a high affinity for oxygen. As oxygen is released to the tissues, the hemoglobin molecule transitions to the **T state (tense state)**, which has a lower affinity for oxygen.\r\n\r\nThe binding and release of oxygen by hemoglobin are crucial for its role in transporting oxygen from the lungs to the tissues and facilitating oxygen exchange in the body.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 26, 28.","responses":[{"text":"4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"16","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11714,"text":"What is secreted as a result of degranulation of platelets?","explanation":"Platelets contain small granules called **alpha granules**, which store various substances involved in platelet function and coagulation. When platelets are activated and undergo degranulation, the contents of the alpha granules are released into the surrounding environment.\r\n\r\n**Thromboxane A2** is one of the substances released from the alpha granules. It is a **potent vasoconstrictor** and **platelet aggregator**, meaning it helps to constrict blood vessels and promote platelet aggregation, which is important for hemostasis and the formation of blood clots at the site of injury.\r\n\r\nThe release of thromboxane A2 from activated platelets contributes to the amplification of platelet activation and the initiation of the clotting cascade.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 88, 120.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 419.","responses":[{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO (nitric oxide)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipoxins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO synthase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11715,"text":"Which chains are involved in the formation of hemoglobin A?","explanation":"The chains involved in the formation of **hemoglobin A** are **2 alpha** and **2 beta**.\r\n\r\n**Hemoglobin A (HbA)**, also known as adult hemoglobin, is the predominant form of hemoglobin found in adults. It consists of two alpha chains and two beta chains. The alpha chains are encoded by the HBA1 and HBA2 genes, while the beta chains are encoded by the HBB gene.\r\n\r\nThe combination of alpha and beta chains in hemoglobin A allows for efficient oxygen transport in the bloodstream. Mutations in the genes encoding these chains can lead to various types of hemoglobinopathies, such as sickle cell anemia and beta-thalassemia.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 27.","responses":[{"text":"2 alpha, 2 zeta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha, 2 delta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha, 2 epsilon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha, 2 gamma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha, 2 beta","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11722,"text":"The red pulp of the spleen contains which one of the following?","explanation":"The spleen is divided into two main compartments: the **red pulp** and the **white pulp**. The **red pulp** is responsible for filtering and processing blood, while the **white pulp** is involved in immune responses.\r\n\r\nWithin the red pulp, there are **sinusoids** and **cords of Billroth**. The sinusoids are vascular channels lined by endothelial cells and are involved in the filtration of blood. The cords of Billroth are reticular tissue structures that contain macrophages, lymphocytes, plasma cells, and erythrocytes. These cords help to remove damaged or old red blood cells, as well as pathogens and cellular debris, from the circulation.\r\n\r\nThe white pulp of the spleen is primarily composed of periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths (PALS) surrounding central arterioles. The PALS contain T-lymphocytes and are involved in initiating immune responses to antigens.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Cords of bilroth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central arteriole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PALS (periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11724,"text":"Which antibodies are released during type 2 hypersensitivity reactions?","explanation":"The antibodies released during type 2 hypersensitivity reactions are **IgG and IgM**.\r\n\r\nIn **type 2 hypersensitivity reactions**, the immune system mistakenly recognizes self-antigens or altered host cells as foreign and produces antibodies against them. These antibodies, mainly IgG and IgM, bind to antigens present on the surface of target cells, leading to their destruction through various mechanisms such as complement activation, opsonization, and antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity (ADCC).\r\n\r\n**IgG antibodies** play a significant role in type 2 hypersensitivity reactions due to their ability to activate complement pathways, bind to Fc receptors on phagocytic cells, and facilitate clearance of antibody-bound cells.\r\n\r\n**IgM antibodies**, although less prevalent than IgG, are also involved in type 2 hypersensitivity reactions. They are typically the first antibodies produced in response to an antigenic stimulus and can activate complement pathways.\r\n\r\nIgE antibodies are associated with type 1 hypersensitivity reactions, not type 2. IgE-mediated hypersensitivity involves the activation of mast cells and basophils, leading to the release of histamine and other inflammatory mediators.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 209.","responses":[{"text":"IgG + IgM","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG + IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD + IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM + IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA + IgE","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11725,"text":"What is the most important value measured from a cross-sectional study?","explanation":"The most important value measured from a cross-sectional study is **prevalence**.\r\n\r\nIn a **cross-sectional study**, data is collected from a population at a specific point in time to determine the prevalence of a particular condition or characteristic within that population. Prevalence represents the proportion of individuals in the population who have the condition of interest at a given time.\r\n\r\nPrevalence provides information about the burden or extent of a condition in the population. It helps in understanding the overall frequency and distribution of the condition, which is important for public health planning, resource allocation, and estimating the disease burden on a population level.\r\n\r\nWhile other measures such as risk, odds ratio, and incidence are also important in epidemiological studies, they are typically calculated and interpreted in other study designs such as cohort studies or case-control studies, which focus on the temporal relationship between exposure and outcome.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 258.","responses":[{"text":"Prevalence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Odds ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incidence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11726,"text":"Which of the following prevents blood loss in a girl who got a cut on her finger?","explanation":"The primary mechanism that would prevent blood loss in the girl with a cut on her finger is the formation of a **platelet plug**. When blood vessels are damaged, platelets in the blood are activated and adhere to the site of injury to form a plug. This process, known as **primary hemostasis**, involves several steps:\r\n\r\n**Vasoconstriction**: Immediately after injury, the blood vessels constrict to reduce blood flow and limit bleeding. This is a rapid response that helps minimize blood loss.\r\n**Platelet adhesion**: Platelets adhere to the exposed collagen fibers at the site of injury, facilitated by the von Willebrand factor (vWF) released by damaged endothelial cells.\r\n**Platelet activation**: Adhered platelets become activated, changing their shape and releasing granules containing substances such as ADP and thromboxane A2. These substances further enhance platelet aggregation and recruitment.\r\n**Platelet aggregation**: Activated platelets aggregate together, forming a platelet plug that partially seals the damaged blood vessel","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 118.","responses":[{"text":"Secondary plug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet plug","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoconcentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrin formation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11727,"text":"Pyridoxamine, pyridoxine, and pyridoxal are forms of which vitamin?","explanation":"**Pyridoxamine, pyridoxine**, and **pyridoxal** are all forms of **vitamin B6**. **Vitamin B6** is a water-soluble vitamin that plays a crucial role in various physiological processes in the body.\r\n\r\nVitamin B6 is involved in the metabolism of proteins, carbohydrates, and fats. It acts as a coenzyme in many enzymatic reactions, particularly those involved in amino acid metabolism. Pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), the active form of vitamin B6, participates in reactions such as transamination, decarboxylation, and synthesis of neurotransmitters.\r\n\r\nDeficiency of vitamin B6 can lead to various neurological symptoms, including peripheral neuropathy, dermatitis, and anemia. Good dietary sources of vitamin B6 include meat, fish, poultry, legumes, nuts, and fortified cereals.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 382.","responses":[{"text":"B3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B6","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B9","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11728,"text":"Palatine tonsil is derived from which of the following?","explanation":"The **palatine tonsil** is derived from the **2nd pharyngeal pouch** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nDuring early development, the pharyngeal arches and pouches contribute to the formation of various structures in the head and neck region. The 2nd pharyngeal pouch gives rise to several important structures, including the palatine tonsils.\r\n\r\nThe palatine tonsils are a pair of lymphoid organs located on the lateral walls of the oropharynx. They play a role in the immune response by filtering and trapping pathogens that enter the body through the oral cavity.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 161.","responses":[{"text":"1st pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd pharyngeal pouch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd pharyngeal arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd pharyngeal arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11743,"text":"Which lymphocyte can destroy cancer cells without having to go through sensitization and hence is able to kill cancer cells in the first line of defense?","explanation":"**Natural killer (NK) cells** can destroy cancer cells without requiring sensitization, making them able to kill **cancer cells** in the **first line of defense**.\r\n\r\nNK cells are a type of lymphocyte that are part of the innate immune system. Unlike T and B lymphocytes, NK cells do not require prior sensitization or the presence of specific antigens to recognize and eliminate target cells, including cancer cells.\r\n\r\nNK cells have the ability to recognize and directly kill abnormal cells, including cancer cells, through various mechanisms. They possess receptors that can detect changes in the expression of surface molecules on target cells, such as downregulation of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class I molecules. This recognition triggers the release of cytotoxic granules containing perforin and granzymes, leading to cell death.\r\n\r\nThe ability of NK cells to target cancer cells without prior sensitization makes them important components of the innate immune response against cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 311.","responses":[{"text":"CD8+ T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural killer cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CD4+ T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11744,"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis is an example of which type of hypersensitivity reaction?","explanation":"**Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (PSGN)** is an example of **type 3 hypersensitivity reaction**.\r\n\r\nType 3 hypersensitivity reactions are characterized by the formation of immune complexes consisting of antigens and antibodies. In the case of PSGN, it occurs as a result of a preceding infection with certain strains of group A beta-hemolytic streptococci, such as Streptococcus pyogenes, which causes pharyngitis or impetigo. During the infection, immune complexes are formed and deposited in the glomerular basement membrane, leading to inflammation and damage to the glomeruli.\r\n\r\nThe immune complexes activate complement and attract neutrophils, resulting in an inflammatory response within the glomeruli. The inflammation can lead to impaired renal function and the characteristic clinical features of PSGN, including hematuria, proteinuria, and edema.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 211.","responses":[{"text":"Type 2 and 3 hypersensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 3 hypersensitivity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2 hypersensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 hypersensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 4 hypersensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11745,"text":"Which of the following factors initiates the extrinsic pathway of clotting?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 479, 481, 483.","responses":[{"text":"Factor III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11746,"text":"What of the following is the iron transporter protein in the plasma?","explanation":"**Transferrin** is a glycoprotein that plays a crucial role in **iron transport** and **homeostasis**. It binds to iron in the bloodstream, forming a complex called transferrin-iron. This complex helps transport iron from sites of absorption (such as the intestines) or storage (such as macrophages) to cells throughout the body that require iron for various functions.\r\n\r\nTransferrin binds to iron with high affinity and specificity, protecting it from oxidation and precipitation. It is responsible for delivering iron to target tissues, including developing red blood cells in the bone marrow.\r\n\r\nHemosiderin is an intracellular complex of iron and protein that serves as a storage form of iron within cells, particularly in macrophages.\r\nApoferritin is the protein component of ferritin and is involved in iron storage within cells.\r\nApotransferrin is transferrin without bound iron, representing the iron-free form of the protein.\r\nFerritin is an intracellular protein complex that serves as the primary storage form of iron within cells.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 64.","responses":[{"text":"Apotransferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11747,"text":"Erythropoietin is produced in kidneys and other cells. What is the second major source of its production?","explanation":"While the primary site of **erythropoietin (EPO)** production is the **kidneys**, the second major source of its production is the **liver**.\r\n\r\nEPO is a glycoprotein hormone that regulates the production of red blood cells. It stimulates the proliferation and differentiation of erythroid progenitor cells in the bone marrow, leading to increased red blood cell production.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the kidneys, the liver is capable of producing and releasing EPO, although to a lesser extent compared to the kidneys. Hepatocytes (liver cells) can synthesize EPO in response to hypoxia (low oxygen levels) or other stimuli.\r\n\r\nThe production of EPO by the liver is considered an adaptive response to tissue hypoxia and anemia. In certain pathological conditions, such as chronic kidney disease, where the kidneys may be compromised, the liver plays a more significant role in EPO production to compensate for the decreased renal EPO synthesis.\r\n\r\nThe stomach, bones, adrenal medulla, and adrenal cortex do not have a significant role in the production of erythropoietin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11752,"text":"The deficiency of which of the following enzymes causes erythropoietic protoporphyria?","explanation":"**Erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP)** is caused by a deficiency of the enzyme **ferrochelatase**.\r\n\r\n**Ferrochelatase** is the final enzyme in the **heme biosynthesis pathway**. It catalyzes the insertion of ferrous iron (Fe2+) into protoporphyrin to form heme. In EPP, there is a genetic defect in ferrochelatase, leading to reduced activity or functional impairment of the enzyme. As a result, there is an accumulation of protoporphyrin in the bone marrow, red blood cells, and other tissues.\r\n\r\nThe excessive accumulation of protoporphyrin in EPP can cause photosensitivity, leading to severe skin reactions upon exposure to sunlight. Patients with EPP may experience symptoms such as burning pain, erythema (redness), edema (swelling), and blistering of the skin after sun exposure.\r\n\r\nThe other enzymes mentioned, such as uroporphyrinogen oxidase, ALA synthase, uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase, and HMB synthase, are involved in other steps of the heme biosynthesis pathway but are not directly related to the development of EPP.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Uroporhyrinogen decarboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HMB synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ALA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporhyrinogen oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11753,"text":"Complete lack of glucuronidation results in which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Crigler-Najjar syndrome** is the disease characterized by a **complete lack of glucuronidation**.\r\n\r\n**Glucuronidation** is a process in which glucuronic acid is attached to various substances, such as bilirubin, drugs, and toxins, to make them more water-soluble and facilitate their excretion from the body. This process is catalyzed by the enzyme **UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT)**.\r\n\r\nIn Crigler-Najjar syndrome, there is a deficiency or absence of the enzyme UGT, leading to impaired glucuronidation. This results in the accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin in the blood, causing a condition known as unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia.\r\n\r\nCrigler-Najjar syndrome is classified into two types: type 1 and type 2. Type 1 is a severe form characterized by a complete absence of UGT activity, leading to extremely high levels of unconjugated bilirubin. It requires lifelong treatment with phototherapy or liver transplantation. Type 2 is a milder form with reduced UGT activity.\r\n\r\nDubin-Johnson syndrome is a separate condition characterized by impaired hepatic excretion of conjugated bilirubin, resulting in its accumulation within hepatocytes. Gilbert syndrome is a benign condition characterized by mild unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. Ehlers-Danlos syndrome is a group of genetic disorders affecting connective tissue. Alport syndrome is an inherited disorder affecting the kidneys and various other organs.","reference":"Bhandari J, Thada PK, Yadav D. Crigler najjar syndrome. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562171/","responses":[{"text":"Crigler Najjar syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gilbert syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ehlers–Danlos syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dubin Johnson syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alport syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11754,"text":"Which of the following is attached to unconjugated bilirubin to form conjugated bilirubin?","explanation":"**Conjugated bilirubin** is formed when **glucuronic acid** is attached to unconjugated bilirubin.\r\n\r\nUnconjugated bilirubin is a product of heme breakdown that is released from aged red blood cells. It is insoluble in water and must undergo a process called conjugation to become water-soluble and suitable for excretion.\r\n\r\nIn the liver, unconjugated bilirubin is taken up by hepatocytes, where it undergoes conjugation. The enzyme responsible for this process is called **UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT)**. UGT catalyzes the transfer of glucuronic acid from UDP-glucuronic acid to unconjugated bilirubin, forming conjugated bilirubin.\r\n\r\nConjugated bilirubin is then secreted into the bile canaliculi and eventually reaches the intestines. In the intestines, it undergoes further metabolism by gut bacteria, leading to the production of urobilinogen, which can be further metabolized into stercobilin or reabsorbed into the bloodstream.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucuronic acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11755,"text":"Which protein shows the highest storage reserves of iron?","explanation":"**Ferritin** is a protein that plays a critical role in **iron storage** within cells. It acts as an intracellular iron-binding protein and serves as the primary storage form of iron in the body. Ferritin molecules can sequester large amounts of iron in a non-toxic and bioavailable form.\r\n\r\nWhen iron levels are high, excess iron is stored in the form of ferritin within cells, primarily in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow. Ferritin allows for the controlled release of iron based on the body's demand, helping to maintain iron homeostasis.\r\n\r\nHaptoglobin is a protein that binds free hemoglobin released during red blood cell breakdown and prevents its toxic effects. Hemosiderin is an insoluble form of iron storage that accumulates in tissues when iron levels are excessive. Hemoglobin is responsible for oxygen transport in red blood cells and does not have storage reserves of iron. Transferrin is a transport protein that binds iron in the blood and facilitates its delivery to cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11756,"text":"Deficiency of which of the following enzymes causes protoporphyria?","explanation":"Deficiency of **ferrochelatase** is responsible for **protoporphyria**.\r\n\r\nPorphyrias are a group of inherited disorders characterized by defects in the enzymes involved in heme biosynthesis. Protoporphyria, specifically, is caused by a deficiency of ferrochelatase, the enzyme responsible for the final step in heme synthesis.\r\n\r\n**Ferrochelatase** catalyzes the insertion of iron (Fe2+) into protoporphyrin to form heme. In its absence or deficiency, there is an accumulation of protoporphyrin in various tissues and body fluids, leading to the characteristic clinical features of **protoporphyria**.\r\n\r\nPatients with protoporphyria may experience photosensitivity, with symptoms such as skin pain, erythema, and edema upon exposure to sunlight. In severe cases, liver dysfunction and gallstones may also occur.\r\n\r\nOther porphyrias result from deficiencies in different enzymes involved in the heme biosynthetic pathway, such as uroporphyrinogen oxidase, ALA synthase, uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase, and HMB synthase. Each type of porphyria is associated with specific enzyme deficiencies and distinctive clinical features.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HMB synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ALA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11757,"text":"Which of the following complement proteins is used to detect the activity of the immune system?","explanation":"**C1q** is the complement protein used to detect the **activity of the immune system**.\r\n\r\nThe complement system is a group of proteins that play a crucial role in the immune response. Activation of the complement system can occur through various pathways, and one of the primary initiators is the binding of C1q to antibodies that have recognized antigens (immune complexes) or directly to microbial surfaces.\r\n\r\nC1q is the first component of the classical pathway of complement activation. It forms a complex with C1r and C1s, which leads to the sequential activation of other complement proteins, including C2, C3, C4, and so on. Activation of the complement system triggers a cascade of reactions, resulting in inflammation, opsonization, and lysis of target cells.\r\n\r\nMeasuring the activity of C1q can provide insights into the activation of the immune system, particularly the classical pathway of complement activation. It is commonly used in laboratory tests to assess immune function and detect complement deficiencies or abnormalities.","reference":"Charles A Janeway J, Travers P, Walport M, Shlomchik MJ. The complement system and innate immunity. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. Published 2001. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27100/","responses":[{"text":"C2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1q","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11759,"text":"Most of the normal human blood is composed of which of the following?","explanation":"Most of the normal human blood is composed of **plasma**.\r\n\r\nPlasma is the **liquid** component of blood, accounting for approximately **55%** of the total blood volume. It is a yellowish fluid that makes up the majority of the non-cellular portion of blood. Plasma is composed mainly of water (approximately 90%) along with various dissolved substances, including proteins, electrolytes, nutrients, hormones, waste products, gases, and other molecules.\r\n\r\nThe cellular components of blood, such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets, constitute the remaining 45% of the blood volume. However, these cellular components are present in smaller quantities compared to the plasma.\r\n\r\nRBCs are responsible for carrying oxygen to tissues, WBCs are involved in immune responses, and platelets are important for blood clotting. Clotting factors, which are proteins, are present in the plasma and are crucial for the process of blood clot formation.\r\n\r\nHowever, in terms of volume, plasma is the major component of human blood.","reference":"Dean L. Blood and the cells it contains. Published 2005. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2263/","responses":[{"text":"Clotting factors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"WBCs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"RBCs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11760,"text":"Which of these is not a cardinal sign of inflammation?","explanation":"Confusion is not a cardinal sign of inflammation.\r\n\r\nThe cardinal signs of inflammation are a set of classic clinical manifestations that are commonly observed during an inflammatory response. These signs include:\r\n\r\n**Swelling (Tumor)**: Swelling occurs due to increased vascular permeability and the accumulation of fluid in the affected tissue.\r\n**Redness (Rubor)**: Redness results from increased blood flow to the inflamed area, leading to dilation of blood vessels (vasodilation).\r\n**Warmth (Calor)**: Warmth is a result of increased blood flow and metabolic activity in the inflamed area.\r\n**Pain (Dolor)**: Pain is caused by the release of chemical mediators and the activation of sensory nerve fibers, sensitizing the area and causing discomfort or tenderness.\r\n\r\nThese signs reflect the body's response to tissue injury or infection and are part of the inflammatory process. Confusion, however, is not a characteristic sign associated with inflammation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 71.","responses":[{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Warmth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Redness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11761,"text":"In smaller vessels, platelets are responsible for vasoconstriction by releasing which of the following?","explanation":"In smaller vessels, platelets play a crucial role in vasoconstriction by releasing thromboxane A2.\r\n\r\n**Thromboxane A2** is a **potent vasoconstrictor** and **platelet aggregator** that is synthesized from arachidonic acid via the action of the enzyme **cyclooxygenase (COX)** in platelets. When platelets are activated, they release thromboxane A2, which acts locally to constrict blood vessels, reducing blood flow and promoting platelet aggregation at the site of injury.\r\n\r\nThe release of thromboxane A2 by activated platelets serves as an important positive feedback mechanism in hemostasis and clot formation. By constricting blood vessels, it helps to minimize bleeding and maintain the integrity of the damaged blood vessel.\r\n\r\nNO (nitric oxide), PG-E2 (prostaglandin E2), prostacyclin, and ADP (adenosine diphosphate), have different roles in the regulation of vascular tone and platelet function. They are primarily involved in vasodilation, inhibition of platelet aggregation, and modulation of clotting processes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PG-E2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostacyclin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11762,"text":"According to the report published in a newspaper regarding the cholera outbreak and a large number of patients were brought to the emergency department with diarrhea, vomiting, and fever. The district house officer asked one of his team members to investigate. What is the first step in the outbreak investigation?","explanation":"In the **investigation of a cholera outbreak**, the first step would be the **verification of diagnosis**.\r\n\r\nVerification of diagnosis involves **confirming** that the cases presenting with symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting, and fever are indeed consistent with the diagnosis of cholera. Cholera is an infectious disease caused by the bacterium Vibrio cholerae, which leads to severe watery diarrhea and can result in dehydration and electrolyte imbalance.\r\n\r\nTo verify the diagnosis, laboratory tests, such as stool culture or rapid diagnostic tests, can be performed to detect the presence of Vibrio cholerae or its toxins in the stool samples of affected individuals.\r\n\r\nOnce the diagnosis is confirmed in a subset of cases, it provides evidence that the outbreak might be due to cholera and allows for appropriate public health interventions to be implemented to control the spread of the disease.\r\n\r\nThe subsequent steps in the outbreak investigation would involve confirming the existence of the outbreak, determining the number of cases and deaths, writing a report, and confirming all cases as part of a comprehensive investigation.","reference":"Fricker RD, Rigdon SE. Investigating a disease outbreak. Significance (Oxford, England). Published April 2020. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7169535/","responses":[{"text":"Write the report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confirmation of the existence of outbreak","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confirm number of deaths","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confirmation of all cases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Verification of diagnosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11763,"text":"In heme synthesis, Fe2+ is added to protoporphyrin to form heme. Which enzyme is needed for this process?","explanation":"In heme synthesis, the addition of Fe2+ (iron) to protoporphyrin to form heme requires the enzyme **ferrochelatase**.\r\n\r\nHeme synthesis is a complex process that occurs mainly in the mitochondria and involves several enzymatic steps. Protoporphyrin, a precursor molecule, undergoes a series of reactions to eventually form heme, which is an essential component of hemoglobin and other heme-containing proteins.\r\n\r\nFerrochelatase is the final enzyme in the **heme synthesis pathway**. It catalyzes the insertion of Fe2+ into protoporphyrin to generate heme. This step is crucial for the proper functioning of hemoglobin, which binds oxygen in red blood cells.\r\n\r\nThe other enzymes such as ferrosynthase, ferrocarboxylase, and ferrohydroxylase, are not specifically involved in the process of adding iron to protoporphyrin during heme synthesis.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrooxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrohydroxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrocarboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrosynthase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11764,"text":"Which type of hemoglobin (Hb) is present in greater than normal amounts in beta-thalassemia minor?","explanation":"In **beta-thalassemia minor**, an inherited blood disorder, there is a reduced production of beta-globin chains, leading to an imbalance in the synthesis of hemoglobin (Hb) chains. As a compensatory mechanism, there is an increased production of other types of hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nIn beta-thalassemia minor, the type of hemoglobin that is present in greater than normal amounts is **HbA2**. HbA2 is a minor form of adult hemoglobin that consists of two alpha-globin chains and two delta-globin chains.\r\n\r\nHbA, the major form of adult hemoglobin, is usually present in normal amounts in beta-thalassemia minor.\r\n\r\nHbS is the abnormal hemoglobin found in sickle cell anemia.\r\n\r\nHbF, also known as fetal hemoglobin, is the predominant type of hemoglobin during fetal development but is reduced in adults. Its levels are typically not significantly increased in beta-thalassemia minor.\r\n\r\nHbC is another abnormal hemoglobin variant associated with a different type of hemoglobinopathy and is not specifically related to beta-thalassemia minor.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 647.","responses":[{"text":"HbF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11765,"text":"In erythroblastosis fetalis, which cells become abundant in the blood culture?","explanation":"In **erythroblastosis fetalis**, also known as **hemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN)**, the **red blood cells** become abundant in the blood culture.\r\n\r\nErythroblastosis fetalis occurs when there is an incompatibility between the blood types of the mother and fetus, most commonly due to Rh factor (Rh incompatibility). If the mother is Rh-negative and the fetus is Rh-positive, the mother's immune system may produce antibodies against the Rh antigen present on the fetal red blood cells.\r\n\r\nThese maternal antibodies can cross the placenta and cause destruction of fetal red blood cells, leading to hemolysis. As a compensatory mechanism, the fetal bone marrow increases its production of red blood cells, resulting in an abundance of immature red blood cells, known as erythroblasts, in the blood.\r\n\r\nIn blood cultures from infants with erythroblastosis fetalis, the presence of these erythroblasts is a characteristic finding.\r\n\r\nMonocytes, T-cells, B-cells, and other immune cells may also be present in the blood culture, but their abundance is not specifically associated with erythroblastosis fetalis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 464.","responses":[{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11766,"text":"Secondary prevention is the method that helps to prevent any disease or injury. Which of the following is a type of secondary prevention?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kisling LA, M Das J. Prevention strategies. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537222/","responses":[{"text":"Health education regarding routine immunization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treatment after a myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Screening for breast cancer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prohibition of driving without driving license","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rehabilitation therapy after amputation of leg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11767,"text":"A 20-year-old male has a history of sickle cell anemia and has repeated 2-year transfusions with a hemoglobin concentration of 8.0 g/dl. Which hemoglobin has a protective effect?","explanation":"In the context of **sickle cell anemia**, the hemoglobin that has a protective effect is **HbF (fetal hemoglobin)**.\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of abnormal hemoglobin known as HbS. This abnormal hemoglobin causes red blood cells to become sickle-shaped and less flexible, leading to various complications.\r\n\r\nHbF, which is the predominant hemoglobin during fetal development, has a protective effect in sickle cell anemia. HbF **inhibits** the **polymerization of HbS**, reducing the tendency of red blood cells to sickle and helping to maintain their normal shape and flexibility. This provides some protection against the complications associated with sickle cell anemia.\r\n\r\nOver time, the production of HbF decreases, and adult hemoglobin, primarily HbA, becomes the predominant hemoglobin in individuals without sickle cell disease.\r\n\r\nHbA2 and HbC are not directly associated with a protective effect in sickle cell anemia. HbA2 is a minor form of adult hemoglobin, while HbC is another abnormal hemoglobin variant that can cause a different type of hemoglobinopathy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 641.","responses":[{"text":"HbC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11768,"text":"Which vitamin deficiency causes anemia?","explanation":"A deficiency of **folic acid**, also known as **vitamin B9**, can cause **anemia**. Folic acid is essential for the production and maturation of red blood cells in the bone marrow. It plays a crucial role in **DNA synthesis** and cell division, including the production of new red blood cells.\r\n\r\nIn the absence of an adequate supply of folic acid, the maturation of red blood cells is impaired, leading to megaloblastic anemia. Megaloblastic anemia is characterized by the presence of large, immature red blood cells (megaloblasts) in the bone marrow. These abnormal cells are unable to function properly, resulting in a reduced oxygen-carrying capacity and the development of anemia.\r\n\r\nPantothenic acid, biotin, ascorbic acid (vitamin C), and β-carotene are not primarily associated with causing anemia. Pantothenic acid and biotin are involved in various metabolic processes, while ascorbic acid and β-carotene have roles in antioxidant function and vitamin A metabolism, respectively.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Β-carotene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pantothenic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biotin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11769,"text":"Which statement best describes an adenoma?","explanation":"An **adenoma** is best described as a **benign epithelial neoplasm of glands**. It is a neoplasm that arises from glandular epithelial cells. Adenomas typically exhibit glandular or tubular architecture and are composed of well-differentiated cells that closely resemble the normal glandular tissue of origin.\r\n\r\nUnlike a carcinoma, which is a malignant tumor, adenomas are considered benign. However, adenomas have the potential to progress to malignancy in some cases, depending on various factors such as size, histological features, and location. The transformation of an adenoma to a carcinoma is often associated with the accumulation of genetic alterations and dysregulated cell growth.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 268.","responses":[{"text":"A benign carcinoma of muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A malignant epithelial carcinoma of glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A benign carcinoma of fibrous tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A benign carcinoma of cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A benign epithelial carcinoma of glands","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11771,"text":"A girl is brought to the outpatient department with complaints of gum bleeding, and epistaxis. Her complete blood count (CBC) shows a normal platelet count and prolonged bleeding time. There is a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"This girl with gum bleeding, epistaxis, normal platelet count, prolonged bleeding time, and a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising most likely has **Glanzmann thrombasthenia**.\r\n\r\n**Glanzmann thrombasthenia** is an inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of the platelet **glycoprotein IIb/IIIa** (integrin αIIbβ3), which is essential for **platelet aggregation**. In this condition, platelets are unable to bind fibrinogen and form stable platelet plugs, leading to impaired clot formation and increased bleeding tendency.\r\n\r\nThe normal platelet count in Glanzmann thrombasthenia distinguishes it from other platelet disorders associated with thrombocytopenia. The prolonged bleeding time is a result of the defective platelet function.\r\n\r\nThe family history of a younger sister with easy bruising suggests an inherited condition. Glanzmann thrombasthenia is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning both parents are carriers of the mutated gene.\r\n\r\nThe other answer choices listed, such as drug-induced thrombocytopenia, hemophilia, immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP), and vitamin K deficiency, do not correlate with the presented clinical features and family history.","reference":"(1) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 434.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 660.","responses":[{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug induced thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glanzmann thrombasthenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11772,"text":"A patient has been diagnosed with a malignant eye tumor in the upper right eye. His molecular analysis shows deletion of both copies of the tumor suppressor gene that checks the transition from the G1 to S phase of the cell cycle. Which of the following genes is defective?","explanation":"In the given scenario, the deletion of both copies of the tumor suppressor gene that checks the transition from the G1 to S phase of the cell cycle suggests a defect in the **Rb-gene (retinoblastoma gene)**.\r\n\r\nThe Rb-gene encodes for the retinoblastoma protein (pRb), which plays a crucial role in regulating the cell cycle by inhibiting the progression from the G1 phase to the S phase. The pRb protein acts as a tumor suppressor by binding to and inactivating transcription factors involved in cell cycle progression.\r\n\r\nWhen both copies of the Rb-gene are deleted or mutated, as seen in this case, there is a loss of the inhibitory function of pRb. This loss of regulation leads to uncontrolled cell proliferation and an increased risk of developing tumors, including **retinoblastoma**, a **malignant eye tumor**.\r\n\r\nNF1 is associated with neurofibromatosis type 1, a condition characterized by multiple benign tumors of neural origin.\r\n\r\nK-Ras is an oncogene commonly associated with various cancers, but it is not specifically related to the G1 to S phase transition of the cell cycle.\r\n\r\nBCl-2 is an anti-apoptotic gene involved in regulating programmed cell death (apoptosis), and its dysregulation is associated with certain cancers, but it is not directly involved in the G1 to S phase transition.\r\n\r\np53 is another tumor suppressor gene involved in regulating the cell cycle and preventing the formation of tumors, but it is not primarily associated with the G1 to S phase transition of the cell cycle.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 291.","responses":[{"text":"NF1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rb-gene","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"K-Ras","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p53","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BCl-2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11773,"text":"Which of the following terms refers to the constant presence of a disease or infectious agent within a given geographical area or population group?","explanation":"The term that refers to the **constant presence** of a disease or infectious agent within a given geographical area or population group is **endemic**. Endemic diseases are those that are habitually present at a **baseline level** within a specific region or population.\r\n\r\nIn an endemic situation, the disease or infectious agent is consistently present and maintained within the population without the need for external introductions. The prevalence of the disease remains relatively stable over time within the defined area or population.\r\n\r\nSporadic refers to the occurrence of isolated cases of a disease that are scattered or irregularly distributed in terms of time and place.\r\n\r\nExotic refers to diseases that are not native to a particular region or population and are introduced from outside.\r\n\r\nPandemic refers to the worldwide spread of a new disease, affecting large populations across multiple countries or continents.\r\n\r\nEpidemic refers to a sudden increase in the number of cases of a disease above the expected level in a specific population or geographical area.","reference":"Principles of epidemiology: glossary. Published December 20, 2021. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/glossary.html","responses":[{"text":"Epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11774,"text":"Atrophy of stomach mucosa damages the parietal cells that secrete intrinsic factor. This causes which one of the following?","explanation":"The atrophy of stomach mucosa that damages the **parietal cells** responsible for secreting **intrinsic factor** leads to **megaloblastic anemia**. Intrinsic factor is a protein secreted by parietal cells in the stomach that is necessary for the absorption of vitamin B12 in the small intestine.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 is essential for the production of red blood cells and DNA synthesis. In the absence of intrinsic factor, vitamin B12 cannot be properly absorbed, resulting in a deficiency of this important vitamin. Megaloblastic anemia is a type of anemia characterized by the presence of large, immature, and dysfunctional red blood cells in the bone marrow.\r\n\r\nThe large, poorly developed red blood cells are unable to function effectively, leading to various symptoms associated with anemia, such as fatigue, weakness, shortness of breath, and pale skin.\r\n\r\nThe other answer choices listed, such as aplastic anemia, idiopathic aplastic anemia, microcytic hypochromic anemia, and hemolytic anemia, are not directly related to the deficiency of intrinsic factor and vitamin B12 caused by the atrophy of stomach mucosa.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic hypochromic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11822,"text":"Which of the following features of the adaptive immune system produces an\r\nexaggerated response?","explanation":"The **adaptive immune system** is characterized by its ability to recognize and respond to **specific antigens**. This **antigen specificity** allows for a highly targeted immune response against particular pathogens or foreign substances. When an antigen is encountered, the immune system produces a specific response tailored to that antigen.\r\n\r\nThe exaggerated response occurs because of the specificity of the adaptive immune system. Once an immune response is initiated against a specific antigen, the immune cells, such as B cells and T cells, undergo clonal expansion and differentiation to produce a large number of effector cells targeting the antigen. This amplifies the immune response, leading to an exaggerated reaction against the antigen.","reference":"Justiz Vaillant AA, Vashisht R, Zito PM. Immediate hypersensitivity reactions. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513315/","responses":[{"text":"Antibody production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delayed response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediate response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antigen specificity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Memory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11823,"text":"A middle-aged woman with a history of rheumatoid arthritis consults her doctor. On examination, she is found to have splenomegaly. Her laboratory results reveal neutropenia and anemia. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for a middle-aged woman with a history of rheumatoid arthritis, splenomegaly, neutropenia, and anemia is **Felty syndrome**. Felty syndrome is a rare complication of long-standing rheumatoid arthritis characterized by the triad of **rheumatoid arthritis, splenomegaly**, and **neutropenia**.\r\n\r\nIn Felty syndrome, the enlarged spleen (splenomegaly) is thought to sequester and destroy white blood cells, resulting in neutropenia (low neutrophil count). Neutropenia increases the risk of recurrent infections. Additionally, the syndrome can be associated with anemia, which may be due to various factors, including autoimmune destruction of red blood cells or decreased production.\r\n\r\nThe combination of rheumatoid arthritis, splenomegaly, and neutropenia is characteristic of Felty syndrome. Other manifestations that may be present in Felty syndrome include skin ulcers, recurrent infections, and lymphadenopathy.","reference":"(1) Patel R, Akhondi H. Felty syndrome. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546693/\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 476.","responses":[{"text":"Idiopathic aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Felty syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11825,"text":"Learning associated with reinforcement is associated with which of the following?","explanation":"Learning associated with reinforcement is primarily associated with **operant learning**. Operant learning, also known as **instrumental conditioning**, refers to a type of learning in which behavior is modified through the use of rewards or punishments.\r\n\r\nIn operant learning, behaviors are strengthened or weakened based on the consequences that follow them. **Positive reinforcement** involves providing a reward or positive stimulus after a desired behavior occurs, increasing the likelihood of that behavior being repeated in the future. **Negative reinforcement** involves removing an aversive stimulus after a desired behavior, also increasing the likelihood of the behavior being repeated.\r\n\r\nFor example, if a student studies diligently and receives praise or good grades as a result, they are more likely to continue studying in the future. The reinforcement of the positive outcome strengthens the behavior of studying.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, classical conditioning involves learning associations between stimuli and involuntary responses, such as the famous example of Pavlov's dogs associating the sound of a bell with food. Modelling refers to learning by observing and imitating others. Innate behaviors are instinctive and do not require learning.\r\n\r\nWhile stimulus presentation can be part of operant learning, the key element that distinguishes operant learning is the association between behavior and its consequences, specifically reinforcement.","reference":"Staddon JER, Cerutti DT. Operant conditioning. Annual Review of Psychology. Published 2003. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12415075/","responses":[{"text":"Innate behavior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Operant learning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Classical conditioning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulus presenting","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11826,"text":"Which protein does hemoglobin bind to after hemolysis of red blood cells?","explanation":"After hemolysis of red blood cells, hemoglobin binds to **haptoglobin**. **Haptoglobin** is a protein found in the plasma that binds to free hemoglobin released from the ruptured red blood cells.\r\n\r\nHemolysis refers to the breakdown of red blood cells, which can occur due to various causes such as infections, autoimmune disorders, or mechanical trauma. When red blood cells lyse, hemoglobin is released into the bloodstream. In order to prevent the loss of hemoglobin and to facilitate its clearance, haptoglobin binds to the free hemoglobin molecules.\r\n\r\nThe haptoglobin-hemoglobin complex formed after binding allows for the removal of hemoglobin from circulation and its transport to the liver for processing and recycling. The liver breaks down the haptoglobin-hemoglobin complex, and the hemoglobin component is further metabolized into bilirubin.\r\n\r\nThe other options listed, such as ferritin, apoferritin, transferrin, and hemosiderin, are involved in iron metabolism and storage but are not directly involved in binding hemoglobin after hemolysis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 631.","responses":[{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11827,"text":"A 60-year-old patient comes to the clinic with pain in his leg for over a week. He further adds that due to pain, he could not move his leg. He has now developed deep vein thrombosis in his leg. Which of the following factors is most likely responsible for thrombus formation?","explanation":"The development of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the leg of a 60-year-old patient is most likely due to immobilization. Immobilization refers to a state of limited or no physical movement, which can lead to blood stasis and an increased risk of thrombus formation.\r\n\r\nThe patient reports having pain in his leg for over a week, and due to the pain, he could not move his leg effectively. Immobility, especially when prolonged, can disrupt normal blood flow within the veins. Reduced muscle contraction and movement impede the normal pumping action of the calf muscles, which helps propel blood through the deep veins. This stagnant blood flow increases the risk of blood clot formation.\r\n\r\nWhile hyperglycemia and hypoglycemia are both metabolic conditions, they are not directly associated with the development of thrombosis. Surgery can increase the risk of DVT due to factors such as trauma to blood vessels and prolonged immobilization during the recovery period. However, in this case, immobilization itself is the most likely cause of the thrombus formation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 123.","responses":[{"text":"Hypoglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immobilization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surgery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11842,"text":"What is the maximum amount of hemoglobin a red blood cell can concentrate at a given time?","explanation":"The maximum amount of hemoglobin that a red blood cell can concentrate at a given time is approximately 34 g/dL. This value represents the upper limit of hemoglobin concentration that can be achieved within a red blood cell.\r\n\r\nHemoglobin is the protein molecule within red blood cells responsible for carrying oxygen from the lungs to the body tissues. It binds with oxygen in the lungs and releases it in the peripheral tissues. The concentration of hemoglobin within red blood cells determines their oxygen-carrying capacity.\r\n\r\nUnder normal physiological conditions, the average hemoglobin concentration in red blood cells is around 15 g/dL. However, during certain pathological conditions, such as severe dehydration or extreme states of polycythemia, the hemoglobin concentration can rise above the normal range. The upper limit for hemoglobin concentration in red blood cells is approximately 34 g/dL.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 439.","responses":[{"text":"34 g/dL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"15 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"21 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"19 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11843,"text":"A 5-year-old child, who has a history of eczema, develops rhinitis and develops asthma with seasonal change. What is the most likely change seen on the peripheral blood smear?","explanation":"The most likely change seen on the peripheral blood smear in a 5-year-old child with a history of eczema, rhinitis, and seasonal asthma is eosinophilic leukocytosis. Eosinophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of eosinophils in the blood.\r\n\r\nEczema, rhinitis, and asthma are commonly associated with allergic conditions. In allergic reactions, such as seasonal allergies, there is an activation of immune cells, particularly eosinophils. Eosinophils play a significant role in the allergic response, and their numbers increase in response to allergens.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the child's symptoms of rhinitis and asthma with seasonal changes suggest an allergic component to their condition. The presence of eczema further supports an underlying allergic tendency. When allergic reactions occur, eosinophils migrate to the affected tissues and can also be detected in the peripheral blood, resulting in eosinophilic leukocytosis.\r\n\r\nLymphocytosis refers to an increased number of lymphocytes in the blood. While lymphocytes play a role in the immune response, they are not specifically associated with the allergic component seen in this case.\r\n\r\nNeutrophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of neutrophils in the blood. Neutrophils are typically elevated in bacterial infections or other inflammatory conditions, but they are not directly associated with allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nMonocytosis refers to an increased number of monocytes in the blood. Monocytes are involved in the immune response against various pathogens, but they are not specifically related to the allergic manifestations described in the case.\r\n\r\nBasophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of basophils in the blood. Basophils are involved in allergic reactions, but they are not commonly seen in significant numbers in peripheral blood smears.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 584.","responses":[{"text":"Eosinophilic leukocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic leukocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophilic leukocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11844,"text":"Which of the following keeps the clotting factors inactivated in the blood?","explanation":"The glycocalyx of the endothelium is responsible for keeping the clotting factors inactivated in the blood. The glycocalyx is a layer of glycoproteins and glycolipids present on the surface of endothelial cells lining the blood vessels. It acts as a physical barrier between the clotting factors in the blood and the underlying endothelium, preventing their activation and subsequent initiation of the clotting cascade.\r\n\r\nIn the clotting process, the interaction between clotting factors and the vessel wall is essential for the initiation of clot formation. However, the glycocalyx plays a crucial role in maintaining the blood in a non-coagulated state by inhibiting the activation of clotting factors and preventing their adherence to the endothelium.\r\n\r\nWhile the plasma membrane of endothelial cells provides structural support and contains receptors involved in clotting, it is not primarily responsible for inactivating clotting factors.\r\n\r\nThromboxane A2 is a pro-inflammatory mediator and a potent platelet aggregator. It promotes platelet activation and aggregation, but it does not keep clotting factors inactivated in the blood.\r\n\r\nCholesterol on the endothelium primarily plays a role in the development of atherosclerosis and does not directly keep clotting factors inactivated.\r\n\r\nNitric oxide (NO) produced by endothelial cells has antithrombotic properties, but its primary function is vasodilation rather than inactivating clotting factors.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Glycocalyx of endothelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric oxide production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma membrane of endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol on endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2 production","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11845,"text":"A middle-aged male comes to the outpatient department with a low to high-grade fever that has been on and off for the last year and has lymphadenopathy. Lymph nodes are discrete, enlarged, non-tender, and have a rubbery consistency. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this case is Hodgkin lymphoma. Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of lymphoma characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells, which are abnormal, large, multinucleated cells. It commonly presents with painless, rubbery, discrete lymphadenopathy, along with other systemic symptoms such as low to high-grade fever, night sweats, and weight loss. The age group affected is usually young adults or middle-aged individuals.\r\n\r\nLeukemia typically presents with symptoms such as fatigue, easy bruising, bleeding tendencies, and anemia. Lymphadenopathy is less prominent in leukemia compared to Hodgkin lymphoma.\r\n\r\nWhile viral infections can cause lymphadenopathy and fever, the chronic nature of the symptoms for a year is not consistent with a simple viral infection.\r\n\r\nSarcoidosis is characterized by non-caseating granulomas that can involve multiple organs. While it can present with lymphadenopathy, the systemic symptoms and rubbery lymph node consistency described in the case are more suggestive of Hodgkin lymphoma.\r\n\r\nConnective tissue disorders such as systemic lupus erythematosus or rheumatoid arthritis can cause lymphadenopathy, but the clinical features described in the case are not typical for these conditions.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 588.\r\n\r\n(2) Mohseni S, Shojaiefard A, Khorgami Z, Alinejad S, Ghorbani A, Ghafouri A. Peripheral lymphadenopathy: approach and diagnostic tools. Iran J Med Sci. 2014;39(2 Suppl):158-170. Accessed May 27, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3993046/","responses":[{"text":"Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Connective tissue disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11846,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for anemia due to reduced erythropoiesis?","explanation":"Aplastic anemia is responsible for anemia due to reduced erythropoiesis. This condition involves a deficiency in the production of red blood cells (RBCs) by the bone marrow. In aplastic anemia, the bone marrow fails to produce an adequate number of RBCs, leading to decreased erythropoiesis and subsequent anemia.\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is a genetic disorder characterized by abnormal hemoglobin molecules, leading to the formation of sickle-shaped RBCs. Although sickle cell anemia can cause anemia, it is primarily due to chronic hemolysis (destruction of RBCs), not reduced erythropoiesis.\r\n\r\nMicroangiopathic hemolysis refers to the destruction of RBCs as they pass through damaged small blood vessels. While this process can result in anemia, it is not primarily caused by reduced erythropoiesis.\r\n\r\nIron deficiency anemia is characterized by a lack of iron, which is necessary for the production of hemoglobin. Although iron deficiency can impair erythropoiesis, it is not primarily due to reduced erythropoiesis itself.\r\n\r\nHereditary spherocytosis is a genetic disorder that causes RBCs to be spherical in shape instead of their normal biconcave shape. While it can lead to anemia, it is not primarily due to reduced erythropoiesis.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 51.","responses":[{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hereditary spherocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

